Hi Rob

On 22-Apr-99, Rob Hutchinson wrote:
> Hello,
> 
>  Ok, me and David McMinn now finished the conversion of the bfbplayer
> C code (Oh thats 2 now ;) oooooooOoooOOo)....

> Anyways, I`ve just finished my SDSBFBPlayer V1.00 (attached), and i`m
> wondering if you nice chappies can test it out before I upload it to
> aminet. It SHOULD in theory support 12 types of module, most of which
> I dont have :(((((.

Me neither - I only have Tracker and Med mods myself.  But I do have
Enforcer...

> Also, can someone test it for inforcer hits for me please, I dont have an
> MMU so I cant do this :(((.

OK, I get a continous stream of Enforcer hits while the program is idle (no
module loaded) - all reads from ...00

If I load a module, everything is OK.  It plays fine, stops, pattern-jumps,
everything fine with no hits.  If I eject the module, the hits start again.

Also there are two hits when a new module is loaded - a read and a write to
...00 or ....01 


> The author of BFB says that Player60A causes
> enforcer hits.

Don't have one to try... 

> But I`m more worried about my routines BFBNextPattern{}
> and BFBPrevPattern{} causing enforcer hits (try pattern jumping in the
> exe pweez). 

No problem with this.

> The reason I think it`ll cause enforcer hits is cos I was
> getting overflow errors from the 2 above commands when overflow checking
> was switched on,.. and it`s fine without. It`s down to the types I think,
> but I couldn`t be arsed to fix it ;)..

Overflow Errors are not "real" errors - it has to do with Blitz's insisting
that all variables are signed.

For example, this will cause an Overflow Error:

a.b=200  because Blitz thinks a byte can only be + or - 127

But the correct byte (or rather bits) is stored anyway:

NPrint a.b AND $FF will return 200.

I always leave overflow errors turned off...

As long as you know the expected result will not exceed the real capacity of
the variable, there's no problem.  And even if you do exceed it, there
won't be any crashes or Enforcer hits - just stupid results returned to
your routines for no apparent reason...

In other words, if you are calling a System routine that needs an unsigned
Word, just turn off overflow errors, put the required number into the Word,
and don't worry about it...

                                    Yours electronically,
                                    Curt Esser
