@NODE "Mail_38" "Re: .res files :("
 for scott@online.u-net.com; Fri, 23 Apr 1999 10:25:17 +0000
From: "David McMinn" <D.Mcminn@eee.rgu.ac.uk>
Organization: The Robert Gordon University, E&EE
Date: Fri, 23 Apr 1999 10:23:13 +0100
encoding: Quoted-printable
Subject: Re: .res files :(

> Thanks a lot that is exactly what i have been after a couple of
> questions though what do the following convert to ?
> 
> typedef 

This doesn't really convert to anything (although I supposed you could use=
 a 
macro). What it does is let the compiler know that it should use a label a=
s a 
variable type:

typedef Node struct Node * is quite common, it means that you can write No=
de 
fff as your variable instead of struct Node *fff.

> #define

defines either a constant or a macro. Anything which is just a number can =
be 
changed to a blitz constant, anthing more complex i.e. has commands, shoul=
d be 
converted into a macro.

> #ifndef
> #endif

#ifndef checks if a label (usually a constant or a macro in C) is defined.=
 If 
not, then it goes into the code between #ifndef and #endif. There's no rea=
l way 
to do this in Blitz, as if something is not defined, the compiler will giv=
e you 
an error message, so you can't check if it is not defined.

> void* is this anything special ?

Its just a general purpose pointer to something. Just use *variable.b


|) /\ \/ ][ |)   |\/| =A9 |\/| ][ |\| |\|
 dmcminn@house-of-mojo.freeserve.co.uk
  http://members.xoom.com/David_McMinn
             ICQ=3D16827694
