@NODE "Mail_39" "Re: 4-bytes -> Long value?"
 for scott@online.u-net.com; Thu, 22 Apr 1999 04:10:52 +0100
From: "Dave" <dave@nbsamiga.demon.co.uk>
Subject: Re: 4-bytes -> Long value?
Date: Thu, 22 Apr 1999 04:10:51 +0100
	charset="iso-8859-1"
Encoding: 7bit

>Hi again,
>
>Right, I'm now off on yet another tangent, trying to parse
>lha files...
>
>The docs tell me that I can get the uncompressed and
>compressed files sizes at certain offsets, and that they're
>stored as 4 bytes.
>
>I basically need to know : how do I turn this 4-byte string,
>ie Edit$ (4), into a long value ? I tried Cvl but that gave a really
>stupid result...
>
>Anyone? Thanks :)


Hmmm..do you have to read them in as a string...are you parsing directly
from the lha file, or from memory??

if you were reading from the file I`d do this when you know that the next 4
bytes in the file is a long....

tmp.l=0                        ;only need to do this once, to setup tmp as a
longword


readmem 0,&tmp,4

asumming your file handle is 0

Hope that helps,

Dave




