@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail_45" "Re: 4-bytes -> Long value?"
 for scott@online.u-net.com; Thu, 22 Apr 1999 13:46:07 +0100
From: "David McMinn" <D.Mcminn@eee.rgu.ac.uk>
Organization: The Robert Gordon University, E&EE
Date: Thu, 22 Apr 1999 13:44:05 +0100
Subject: Re: 4-bytes -> Long value?

--Message-Boundary-20017
encoding: Quoted-printable
Content-description: Mail message body

> Uh-oh...now I can't use your ReadMem method to turn the bytes into
> a longword, because I have to read them as a string now and reverse it -
> any idea how to do what ReadMem does "by hand"...?

ReadMem just takes data straight from the file and sticks it into memory. =
If 
you need to read in as a string, you could just read 4 bytes in at a time,=
 with 
Inkey$(4).

But if you want a little function which converts between endian formats (u=
sing 
strings or longwords, and converts in either direction), there's a small s=
ource 
attached.


|) /\ \/ ][ |)   |\/| =A9 |\/| ][ |\| |\|
 dmcminn@house-of-mojo.freeserve.co.uk
  http://members.xoom.com/David_McMinn
             ICQ=3D16827694
Never argue with an idiot. They drag you down to their
level then beat you with experience.



--Message-Boundary-20017
encoding: 7BIT
Content-description: Text from file 'endian.asc'

x.l=$12345678

Statement endian{*mem.l}
  MOVE.l d0,a0
  MOVE.l (a0),d0
  ROL.w #8,d0
  SWAP d0
  ROL.w #8,d0
  MOVE.l d0,(a0)
End Statement

NPrint "Using a longword"
NPrint "Original x: ",Hex$(x)
endian{&x}
NPrint "Endian converted x: ",Hex$(x)
endian{&x}
NPrint "Back to original: ",Hex$(x)

NPrint ""
NPrint ""
NPrint "Using a string (shown as hex dump)"


z.s=Chr$($32)+Chr$($76)+Chr$($12)+Chr$($09)

NPrint "Original z: ",Hex$(Peek.l(&z))
endian{&z}
NPrint "Endian converted z: ",Hex$(Peek.l(&z))
endian{&z}
NPrint "Back to original: ",Hex$(Peek.l(&z))



--Message-Boundary-20017

