>ReadMem just takes data straight from the file and sticks it into memory.
If
>you need to read in as a string, you could just read 4 bytes in at a time,
with
>Inkey$(4).
>
>But if you want a little function which converts between endian formats
(using
>strings or longwords, and converts in either direction), there's a small
source
>attached.

That`s probably the best way to do it...or you could simply read in the 4
bytes in a different order ie

tmp.l=0

readmem 0,&tmp+3,1:readmem 0,&tmp+2,1:readmem 0,&tmp+1,1:readmem 0,&tmp,1

This wouldn`t take much more time really, as the system buffers disk reads
(a Kb or two probably) and so does blitz, so your not actually reading
directly from the disk byte by byte......but of course doing less readmem
and doing the conversion in memory is faster....you could always do the
longword readmem and use David`s conversion routine on that long
;)....(shouldn`t there be an asmexit at the bottom of that routine
david??)......



Share and Enjoy,

Dave



