@NODE "Mail_59" "Re: A few quick questions"
 for scott@online.u-net.com; Wed, 14 Apr 1999 07:37:56 +0100
From: Curt Esser <camge@ix.netcom.com>
Date: Wed, 14 Apr 1999 01:31:34 -0500
Subject: Re: A few quick questions

--BOUNDARY.1748518056.2

Hi Tony

On 13-Apr-99, Tony Rolfe wrote:
> I've just started using the ASLFileRequest function from Stats&Funcs
> (Curt wrote it first, I think) but I can't get it to show the Pattern
> gadget like the TED Load File Requester.  How do I do that?

It was actually by Paul Burkey - but I've attached a modified version that
shows the pattern gadget.
> 
> Also, how do I get the depth of a screen? is it:
> *Screen/BitMap/Depth or 
> *Screen/*Bitmap/Depth or
> something completely different.
> There's no * in front of the bitmap in the screen newtype so I think
> the first is correct??

Almost - but to access the NewTypes, you must use a "\" rather than "/"
You need to get the pointer yourself first also:

*SCR.Screen=peek.l(addr Screen(0))   ;pointer to screen structure
dpth.b=*SCR\Bitmap\Depth             ;should return the depth

Well, in theory that should work - unfortunately, it doesn't work on my
system...
I tried it with all 3 versions of amigalibs.res, but the Bitmap  (or
_Bitmap) newtype on all 3 seems to be broken.  I can't get it recognized
with any .res version, unless I'm doing this all wrong.  All the other
Screen stuff works, but not the bitmap.

The only way I can get the depth of the WB is by using the Blitz WBdepth
command or by grabbing the Screen's bitmap, and reading the Blitz bitmap
object.
Neither method will work on a GFX card screen, I don't think.

Anybody else gotten this to work?
> 
> I'm going to try to make my GT  GUI font sensitive and also convert
> the program to NCS.   Which should I do first.   My gut feeling is NCS
> first.   Any thoughts?

Yes, convert to NCS first.
> 
> Given that I've got one screen (#0), three windows (#0,1,2) and 47
> GTLists (#guess what??)  when I go NCS, should I try and change all at
> once or do the screen first, then the windows, then the gadgets or the
> gadgets first, then  windows, then screen.   Also,  there is an
> NInitGadget command (plus similar for the windows etc.)   Is the
> argument to this the highest gadget number, the total number of
> gadgets or the number in use simultaneously?

These commands always refer to the total number you will be using (similar
to the settings in the compiler options for standard windows, GTlists,
etc.)

Note that total number assumes you are using them in order, ie if you only
use 1 window, but want to call it window 5 for some reason, you must set it
to 5.  If you call it window 0, set it to 0.

Or, simply, just set it to the highest window number, gadget list number,
screen number, or whatever, that you will be using for that item.



> I.e if I have gadgets numbered 1,3,5,7  with only one in use at any
> time, do I NinitGadget 1, NInitGadget 4 or NInitGadget 7??

No, it is set to the total number of Gadget Lists - if you are using 47
gadgetlists, 0 ~ 46, set it to 46.  It has nothing to do with how many
gadgets are used.


                                    Yours electronically,
                                    Curt Esser
                                    camge@ix.netcom.com
                                    http://members.xoom.com/Curt_Esser/


--BOUNDARY.1748518056.2
Content-Disposition: attachment; filename="ASLreq.asc"
Content-Description: Curt Esser <camge@ix.netcom.com>


; Function : ASLFileRequest { title, path, file, pattern }

; Author : Paul Burkey - burkey@bigfoot.com

; This function uses OS functions to call up the ASL file
; requester.

; You MUST have a screen in use!

; You can configure the size by altering the top,left,
; width and height variables within the function.

; IMPORTANT NOTE!!! You won't see anything different if you're
; using a patch like RTPatch or MCP's Reqtools Patch function!

Function.s ASLFileRequest{title$,pathname$,filename$,pat$}
  *scr.Screen=Peek.l(Addr Screen(Used Screen))

  top.w=0
  left.w=0
  width.w=ScreenWidth/2 ; remove /2 for full-screen requester! ;)
  height.w=ScreenHeight

  Dim Tags.TagItem(10)
  Tags(0)\ti_Tag=#ASLFR_Screen,*scr
  Tags(1)\ti_Tag=#ASLFR_InitialPattern,&pat$
  Tags(2)\ti_Tag=#ASLFR_TitleText,&title$
  Tags(3)\ti_Tag=#ASLFR_InitialFile,&filename$
  Tags(4)\ti_Tag=#ASLFR_InitialDrawer,&pathname$
  Tags(5)\ti_Tag=#ASLFR_InitialLeftEdge,left
  Tags(6)\ti_Tag=#ASLFR_InitialTopEdge,top
  Tags(7)\ti_Tag=#ASLFR_InitialWidth,width
  Tags(8)\ti_Tag=#ASLFR_InitialHeight,height

; to show pattern gadget:

  Tags(9)\ti_Tag=#ASLFR_DoPatterns,-1

  Tags(10)\ti_Tag=#TAG_END,0

  *filereq.FileRequester=AllocAslRequest_(#ASL_FileRequest,&Tags(0))
  If *filereq
    ok.l=AslRequest_(*filereq,&Tags(0))
    If ok
      f$=Peek.s(*filereq\fr_Drawer)
      If f$<>"" Then If Right$(f$,1)<>":" AND Right$(f$,1)<>"/" Then f$=f$+"/"
      f$=f$+Peek.s(*filereq\fr_File)
    EndIf
    FreeAslRequest_(*filereq)
  EndIf
  Function Return f$
End Function

; demo :

 WBenchToFront_

 FindScreen 0

 picked$=ASLFileRequest{"Choose File","s:","shell-startup",""}
 If picked$<>""
   NPrint "You selected: ",picked$
 Else
   NPrint "Requester cancelled!"
 EndIf



 MouseWait
 End



--BOUNDARY.1748518056.2

