Organization: Fantaisie Software
Subject: Re: A possible way to get fast animation & good packing ratio easely
Encoding: quoted-printable

    Hi Paul, =


>>    I've followed your discution about the 'possible' new animation
>> format (in chunky mode) and may be the XPK library can help you becaus=
e
>> it has a real fast/good Packer: NUKE. It depack about 600 kb/sec on a
>> 68030/25 so it should overtake the 1 Mb/s on a 040/25.
>> =

>>    As it packs very well, you should save the each chunky frame in a
>> raw form and pack each independently with NUKE. After, you put all
>> the frames in one single file with extra infos for each frame and
>> you use load/depack one frame each after other directly into
>> the video memory buffer...
> =

> Give it a try! Presently my compression effort is working, albeit
> slowly until I finish converting it to asm. Seems to work fairly well
> but as I expected it is still not all that good on scenes which change
> a lot. It's great on cartoons type anims though. I also haven't
> written a decompressor yet so I'm not entirely sure it compresses
> properly, although it's stopped crashing which is a good sign.
> Compression ratios generally seem to be about 1:3 at the moment. :-\

    Your method sounds very good.

    Yesterday, I'm going further in my anim test and my test 320*200
chunky image was compressed from 64000 to 16000 bytes via the RDCN
XPK packer. It's a good ratio and the depack is very fast (theory:
920 kb/sec) as it has depacked 50 times the picture in 46 ticks
on my 030/050 (depack was in fast ram), so less than 1 ticks.
CopyMemQ from fastram to chip ram took 1 ticks too, and reading
50 times a 16 kb block from the harddisk took 32 ticks.

    So three things togheter took about 2,3 ticks which is about
18 fps on a pal screen 320*200*8.

    The bad news is if the picture is complex, the compression
is bad, even with best (slow) XPK packers (GZIP, ...) on
another picture, RDCN ratio was 3 % (ie: no compressed). The
advantage of the XPK is to not compress the picture (via NONE
packer) and everything works). Or use different packers for
differents pictures in the same anim... =


    After I've tryed to do no compression over pictures. I was surprised
because reading 64000 bytes from HD or from a fast CD-ROm is about the
same:

    50 read to a fastram buffer from an HD (slow Hd :) was about 86 ticks=

(ie: 25 fps !) and from a CD-Rom (32X Pionneer IDE) was 92 ticks
(ie: 25 fps too). Copying the data to chip take always 1 ticks,
 so hum, 18 fps too. Not too bad when you think than each picture can
be totally different from the previous one (ie: movies..)

    And the last test was saving a picture in Raw BitMap format and
load it directly from the HD to the ChipMem buffer:

    113 ticks to load 50 pictures, so 22 fps (coool). But from the
CD-Rom, it tooks 270 ticks ??? I guess it don't have the DMA
activated... Too bad.
    =

    Hope this help,

-- =

                        Fred.

