@NODE "Mail_131" "animation"
 for scott@online.u-net.com; Mon, 5 Apr 1999 16:07:13 +0100
From: "Paul" <paulwest@stationone.demon.co.uk>
Organization: private
Date: 5 Apr 99 15:58:31 +0000
Subject: animation
Encoding: 7bit

Hi folks.

I've been following the animation format discussions and although it
is interesting to be chatting about mpegs and avis and what
specification pc you need to play them at decent rates, and what is
required to play cdxl, it doesn't really address the original problem
which is how to easily play quality animation and possibly also sound
designed for the modern-day Amiga. IMHO cdxl is not a good enough
format and most of the lossy methods such as mpeg and avi require too
much cpu power.

I have been reading up on various animation storage and compression
methods. First and foremost our option is to design a new `anim'
format along the same lines as the anim5, anim7(16/32) and
anim8(16/32) methods. It is clear that the future is to work in
chunky, and this has some good benefits for this kind of animation
format. Firstly, the difference between the 16 and 32 versions of the
IFF anim format are that it either works in words or in longwords.
The anim5 format, however, works in bytes. The thing is that the
format works in and is designed for planar displays and therefore a
single byte spans 8 pixels. Although some benefits may be gained
through the fact that the compression is split up into seperate
bitplanes, it doesn't help to optimise the accuracy of the image
changes. If we were to work in chunky, even a longword-based format
(anim9_32) would allow for changes to 4-pixel groups, and with a
format similar to anim5 it would allow detection of changes to
individual pixel accuracy. Another benefit is that due to working in
fastram it would not be necessary to have the doublebuffered feature
of the IFF anim format, whereby delta frames are based on 2 frames
previous. Working in chunky the deltas could be based on the actual
previous frame which will mean less actual changes between frames
which can help with compression. This sort of format would be fine for
256 colour animations, cell animations, handdrawn stuff and some
raytracing if care is taken with dithering etc, that sort of thing.

There is a method called motion compensation/estimation which is a
process of breaking up the image into blocks of 8x8 or 16x16 for
example. The image is searched for areas which are as similar as
possible and a trigonometric translation is performed (ie a X,Y
offset), which allows compression due to storing only the offsets
rather than the actual pixels. This works okay for things like camera
pans and horizontal or verticle scrolling objects but doesn't help
much when parts of a scene are zoomed or rotated or altered like in a
cartoon perhaps. Other formats have also the capability of
rotation, shear, stretch, etc. Apparently motion compensation is
usually used in combination with some pretty complicated lossy
compression such as in mpeg, but both compression and decompress can
be slow. The general idea of taking other parts of the image and
reusing them could be helpful. 

A similar method is a lookup-table lossy method whereby a tolerance
level is set. Blocks of pixels are compared for their differences and
if the difference is within the tolerance limit then the blocks can be
replaced by a reference to a catalogue of `general blocks'. This
compresses by only having to have references to indexes within the
lookup tables rather than storing all the pixels and playback is quite
good speed but compression can be slow. The data can become more or
less lossy depending on how close you want the block comparisons to
be. 

I think that generally some benefits can be had from working in chunky
and using rtg for display. It allows you to work with smaller groups
of actual pixels which means more accuracy in detecting changes which
can only lead to greater efficiency. Perhaps some ideas also would be
to be able to make palette changes, play samples, and trigger the
loading of whole sections of animation, at particular key frames.

Animation formats such as mpeg have a key frame method whereby the
compression of subsequent frames is based on a key frame. The problem
is that this leads to increasing numbers of errors as the frames tick
over, which is why there are many key frames within a file. I don't
know if something like IFF anim format could be optimised to have more
than one key frame, rather than basing all frames on the first one, or
if there is even any point doing that.  We should also note that
working in longwords we can output data to unaligned addresses, ie
which are not multilpes of 4 bytes, if that could somehow help with
the accuracy of the deltas.

It wouldn't be difficult at all to do a similar format that could work
with lossless data in 15, 16 or 24bit. We do need to think to the
future so supporting at least hi-colour would be desirable. I think
that if we try to do a hi or truecolour format rather than a LUT
format (ie 256 colours colourmap) we will have to get very much more
complicated and could wind up with something that needs too much cpu
time. Working with 256 colours can in some ways help with compression,
compared with lossless hi/truecolour anyway.

Hmm. One idea that just came to me is to have deltas as in IFF anim
format but to let there be an X,Y offset into the data for each
`block' of pixels, rather than or in addition to inserting new data
where the frame changes. Perhaps if we wanted to step into lossy
territory then a delta-offset method would work better there, allowing
a certain loss of accuracy in the block of data used. Also we have to
note that lookup tables of blocks can be accumulated and shared
accross many frames, not just one.

Anyway, there are some ideas about it so far. I personally think we
need a new format that is inbetween IFF anim and the lossy formats. I
don't much like CDXL myself, I think the sound quality is naff and it
doesn't play very fast. Much the same can be said of avi and mov,
which although they play fairly okay speed it still leaves a lot to be
desired and uses lots of cpu beef. mpeg i suppose is okay as a
compressed format but quality isn't usually that good and playback is
slow, especially if you wanted sound also. I don't think it's
feasible to have 16-bit sound and truecolour smooth animation on the
target cpu of 68030/50Mhz. Nor do I particularly think that is
necessary for a decent in-game anim as there should be design and
imagination in the animation itself that transcends the technicality
of how many bits the sound samples are using and how the anim format
works. Most people don't give a dam. Also if I'd created some nice
raytraced animation for a game I wouldn't be sure wether to choose
between making it into an mpeg and have it play pretty slow and with
lossy of quality, or wether to go for a more orderly loss through
dithering down to 256 colours and having it play nice and fast with
crisp edges and accurate motion.

Let us not forget that it would be nice to be able to spool off of
harddrive or more possibly cdrom, and that the cdrom may not be very
fast (although I'm not sure that it would be too useful to target
2xspeeds).  4xspeed would be a better starting point perhaps, and we
must also remember that we have to read in the graphics and sound data
at the same time (pretty much) as playing it. The lossy formats do
help with managing the amount of data going through, but then there is
the inevitable loss of quality and reduction in framerates. Personally
I would opt for accasional strategic delays to load in chunks of data
rather than have to reduce the specification. My target is for 25fps
playback on 030/50 and above in lores working in chunky, perhaps
requiring an 040/25 in order to play 16-bit. Animations really do take
up a lot of room so we really need to come up with some ingenious ways
to cut it down without turning it into a mess.

Let me know how this all grabs ya, any further ideas etc.


-- 
Paul.

IRC: #amiga, Dalnet: #blitz
WWW: http://www.stationone.demon.co.uk
E-M: paul@stationone.demon.co.uk


