@NODE "Mail_132" "Re: animation"
 for scott@online.u-net.com; Tue, 6 Apr 1999 00:07:01 +0000
From: "Dave" <dave@nbsamiga.demon.co.uk>
Subject: Re: animation
Date: Mon, 5 Apr 1999 21:46:08 +0100
	charset="iso-8859-1"
Encoding: 7bit


Hi Paul,


>Hi folks.
>
>I've been following the animation format discussions and although it
>is interesting to be chatting about mpegs and avis and what
>specification pc you need to play them at decent rates, and what is
>required to play cdxl, it doesn't really address the original problem


Awwww...there ya go spoiling all my fun again...and we were justing getting
a nice `discussion`  ;) going................Your no fun anymore!

>which is how to easily play quality animation and possibly also sound
>designed for the modern-day Amiga. IMHO cdxl is not a good enough
>format and most of the lossy methods such as mpeg and avi require too
>much cpu power.

Depends what your after...I`d be happy with 320x200x8 (that`s 256 colours)
at 15fps with 8 bit sound at anywhere between 11khz, and 44khz :) (I don`t
ask for much do I??)....the file size isn`t important to me..it`d be more
important that you could view it at 15fps on a cd32 (ie, 2 speed). An option
is too copy paul, and have a lowres anim, and hires anim, one for slower
computers...but if it`s a big intro...you could be talking 100mb`s files.
The size is important, simply because we`d have to stick to 300k per second
(actually slightly less), and have to get sound and video from the cd. Ie,
for one second you`d have

some headers...maybe 1/2k for 15 frames..
22k of sound (for 22khz at 8 bits mono..right??)
 video (which would be something like the following:
64k for each key frame
0-64k for a line change frame (only saves lines that changed)
0-64k for a box change frame (only saves boxes that changed)
0-64k for a pixel change frame (stores blocks of pixel changes)
32k for a delta frame (if the changes where within a tolerance of -8/+8 of
the last frame)
0k for blank frame)
768 bytes for palette changes

Of course that`s just a simple layout and idea..but it`d need to be simple
and fast. You`d have to have a quality value when encoding (ie, so it
decides a upper and lower limit for more lossy compression)..and a set
ordered palette would help (you could add 16 bit RGB support for future use
and use different encode methods). The problem is that you really need the
whole block for one second to be smaller than your 1 second read limit....of
course...you may will have frame sizes varying, but the reply routine could
compensate for that (but when you break your read limit..you`ll have a small
gap). Plus you need to be able to hold the two biggest one second video
clips in memory at any one time (ie, one your decoding, and a buffer your
reading into!). 15fps gives you a while to do what you need (3 frames to
decode a frame, and c2p it for aga, and load some of the next frame block
into the buffer). If you use better compression, you can get 25fps...but I
think you`d be looking at greater than the 030/50 barrier, or making the
read limit higher...maybe it should be quad speeds cd roms..but then I`ve
just made it not work on a cd32...which I`m sure some people still use :)
(even just as a cd device for their A1200).


>I have been reading up on various animation storage and compression
>methods. First and foremost our option is to design a new `anim'
>format along the same lines as the anim5, anim7(16/32) and
>anim8(16/32) methods.

You could...but then you`d be better off just designed a new format...and
calling it pauls spectacular video format....rather than anim9, as it
wouldn`t work in older software that supports the anim formats, and people
would probably think it`s a throw back to iff ;)

>There is a method called motion compensation/estimation which is a
>process of breaking up the image into blocks of 8x8 or 16x16 for
>example. The image is searched for areas which are as similar as
>possible and a trigonometric translation is performed (ie a X,Y
>offset), which allows compression due to storing only the offsets
>rather than the actual pixels. This works okay for things like camera
>pans and horizontal or verticle scrolling objects but doesn't help
>much when parts of a scene are zoomed or rotated or altered like in a
>cartoon perhaps. Other formats have also the capability of
>rotation, shear, stretch, etc. Apparently motion compensation is
>usually used in combination with some pretty complicated lossy
>compression such as in mpeg, but both compression and decompress can
>be slow. The general idea of taking other parts of the image and
>reusing them could be helpful.


Yes...but it`s very slow....this is not a bad idea however...but I doubt you
could get it working well enough on the amiga. (plus encoding it would take
a longggg time searching for all the possible matches from one frame to
another!). It reminds me of the picture compression thing I saw on bbc2`s
open university late one night ;)

>A similar method is a lookup-table lossy method whereby a tolerance
>level is set. Blocks of pixels are compared for their differences and
>if the difference is within the tolerance limit then the blocks can be
>replaced by a reference to a catalogue of `general blocks'. This
>compresses by only having to have references to indexes within the
>lookup tables rather than storing all the pixels and playback is quite
>good speed but compression can be slow. The data can become more or
>less lossy depending on how close you want the block comparisons to
>be.


I think that`s just like a dictionary compressor isn`t it??...it depends how
big the table would be, but I suppose you could load it at the start (ie, on
have one)..but from then on, all your blocks would have to come from that.
Maybe you could use the blocks as the changes from the previous frame to the
next (but I don`t know if that`d work...but there may be less change values
to store in your lookup). If you could say, store all the 2x2 blocks you
needed in a table of 64k longs which you access with words, you could make
all the frames half size...maybe you could stretch to 4x4, but then you`d
have pretty lossy compression. Unless you mean`t make a new table for each
frame, and just save those pairs...but then I`m not sure how much
compression you`d get.

>I think that generally some benefits can be had from working in chunky
>and using rtg for display. It allows you to work with smaller groups
>of actual pixels which means more accuracy in detecting changes which
>can only lead to greater efficiency. Perhaps some ideas also would be
>to be able to make palette changes, play samples, and trigger the
>loading of whole sections of animation, at particular key frames.


Definetly...chunky I`d say...you could add planar support..but you`d be
better off with chunky, and it works with my 15fps for aga fine..but you`d
be lucky to get 25fps for aga...with a c2p anyway. I`m not so sure about the
play samples/tigger stuff...I personally think you`d be better off adding a
continual soundtrack to it...as the sound (with or without delta
compression) isn`t that big.

>Animation formats such as mpeg have a key frame method whereby the
>compression of subsequent frames is based on a key frame. The problem
>is that this leads to increasing numbers of errors as the frames tick
>over, which is why there are many key frames within a file. I don't
>know if something like IFF anim format could be optimised to have more
>than one key frame, rather than basing all frames on the first one, or
>if there is even any point doing that.  We should also note that
>working in longwords we can output data to unaligned addresses, ie
>which are not multilpes of 4 bytes, if that could somehow help with
>the accuracy of the deltas.


I think you pretty much HAVE to have key frames. If you watch tv for a
while...you`ll see them cutting from one scene to another.....with different
lighting..colours..etc....it would be impossible to do all those changes
fast enough even with mpeg, and it`d no doubt end up bigger than the key
frame size. (basically, the mpeg compressors I`ve used...attempt to
compress..and if the compressed frame is bigger than a key frame..it simply
puts a key frame in...which is why the are so damn slow!)

>It wouldn't be difficult at all to do a similar format that could work
>with lossless data in 15, 16 or 24bit. We do need to think to the
>future so supporting at least hi-colour would be desirable. I think
>that if we try to do a hi or truecolour format rather than a LUT
>format (ie 256 colours colourmap) we will have to get very much more
>complicated and could wind up with something that needs too much cpu
>time. Working with 256 colours can in some ways help with compression,
>compared with lossless hi/truecolour anyway.


It`d be easy to do, you just leave gaps in the file format, and make sure
that people stick to say, V1.0 (which only allows 256 colour paletted anims)
and then when V2.0 is announced, it will be the same format, but the earlier
animplayers will let you know that, and refuse to load...we can simply have
a type...ie

FRAME TYPE = PALETTE / RGB

 then if it was RGB we`d have RGB DEPTH = 16/24/32

Also you`d need different compression types for RGB.

>avi and mov


argrhghghghghg...did I not tell ya once already....avi`s and movs
(quicktime) are just big trucks, for transporting video data, inside them
can be indeo compression, mpeg, vfw etc....lol...no, seriously ;) you can`t
compare 1 avi to another, unless there both the same fps, same size, same
compression codec..

>Let us not forget that it would be nice to be able to spool off of
>harddrive or more possibly cdrom, and that the cdrom may not be very
>fast (although I'm not sure that it would be too useful to target
>2xspeeds).  4xspeed would be a better starting point perhaps, and we
