>  (ie, only
> have one)..but from then on, all your blocks would have to come from that.
> Maybe you could use the blocks as the changes from the previous frame to the
> next (but I don`t know if that`d work...but there may be less change values
> to store in your lookup). If you could say, store all the 2x2 blocks you
> needed in a table of 64k longs which you access with words, you could make
> all the frames half size...maybe you could stretch to 4x4, but then you`d
> have pretty lossy compression. Unless you mean`t make a new table for each
> frame, and just save those pairs...but then I`m not sure how much
> compression you`d get.

Well what i figured is that instead of using this for lossy, why not
keep the past, say, 4 decoded frames, and use them as reference for
`cut and paste' operations, ie your dictionary.
 
> Definetly...chunky I`d say...you could add planar support..but you`d be
> better off with chunky, and it works with my 15fps for aga fine..but you`d
> be lucky to get 25fps for aga...with a c2p anyway.

The c2p on 030/50 runs at 30fps for 320x256 or 40fps for 320x200 if i
recall correctly. So yea, its a fair bit of time, especially if you're
aiming at spooling it off cd.

> I`m not so sure about the
> play samples/tigger stuff...I personally think you`d be better off adding a
> continual soundtrack to it...as the sound (with or without delta
> compression) isn`t that big.

Well modules are pretty okay usually although they dont allow you to
have particularly long sophisticated samples but can be used for most
purposes and then you can tap into their timing to synchronise the
anim playback. I guess we're sort of getting into the realms of those
anim programs like moviesetter and such.

> argrhghghghghg...did I not tell ya once already....avi`s and movs
> (quicktime) are just big trucks, for transporting video data, inside them
> can be indeo compression, mpeg, vfw etc....lol...no, seriously ;) you can`t
> compare 1 avi to another, unless there both the same fps, same size, same
> compression codec..

ok. Generally speaking though my experience of avi's tells me that
they aren't usually all that fast and there is quality loss.

>My target is for 25fps
> >playback on 030/50 and above in lores working in chunky,
> 
> hmmm...320x200??

No fullscreen. Although admittedly 320x200 would help matters somewhat
on an 030.

>  I assume you mean to a video card...it would depend
> how
> long it`d take for a frame to move from fastram to the video ram...I
> think
> 25fps on aga wouldn`t be possible using chunky. A quad speed cd rom
(which
> is more like what we`d need)....is about 600k/sec. 600k/25 frames =
24k per
> frame...without sound...:(

So despite the sound we have to get the animation to have only 24k for
each frame.  320x240 is 78k of data for a full image change, whereas
320x200 is 64k. So we would be looking at something like 3:1
compression ratio. As you say there wouldn't be any room for sound so
that'd be assuming that a module was previously loaded and is being
played, wether that be a tune or just strategic sound samples loaded
in that are being triggered to play by the anim.

Hmm, so if it were to run at 16fps then I suppose you would be able to
have your 22Khz sound sample also. But is it possible to be loading in
data continuously at the same time as decompression and playback? How
about targetting an 6 or 8-speed cd-rom? ;-)

Hmm.. Well, personally I am quite interested in having an animation
format for just anims like what I keep on my harddrive. I find that I
usually have to convert them to anim 7 or 8 in order to get decent
playback and even anim5's can be quite large. So I think I will dabble
with a lossless chunky format with further compression methods in
addition to run length, such as using repetition sequences from
previous frames. Aiming for graphic playback only without sound. You
may be more interested to look into lossy if you know more about that,
I've not really touched it myself. I can see that 15fps looks like a
fairly reasonable target but not without quality loss. Is it
possible to do some kind of simple sound compression? I have never
looked into it.

I am going to start looking into a lossless animation format so maybe
you would like to delve into the lossy cd-rom approach and we'll just
sort of see what application becomes of it all later.


> 
> >perhaps
> >requiring an 040/25 in order to play 16-bit. Animations really do
take
> >up a lot of room so we really need to come up with some ingenious
ways
> >to cut it down without turning it into a mess.
> 
> 
> true...and that`s where I get stuck...the same as everyone else ;)
> 
> >Let me know how this all grabs ya, any further ideas etc.
> 
> 
> Ummmm,
> 
> Dave
> 
> 
