Andreas,

> Errrmm why do you guys want to target those old dinosaurs ? I have a 32x
> cd-rom in my amiga 4000 and a 36x in my work pc. I would have gotten a
> 36x for my amiga as well, but since i bought the amiga cd-rom before the
> 36x was out in the shops Ididnt have much choise..

Well not everyone has taken your path through life and made the
choices you have, so not everyone is going to have modern cd-roms even
if they are cheap nowadays. I did have a 2xspeed for some time and
then moved to a 6xspeed simply because I needed a new one for my tower
conversion and didn't have the extra 20 quid at the time for a 24, and
the company i was wanting to buy from didn't have any other speeds
available. I do agree though that 2xspeed is really pretty anchient.
 
> So you could atleast set 8x as minimum or even make is possible to
> set your own target cd-rom . Having a 060, cybervision ppc 8mb card,
> and a 32x I would love a anim format with cd-audio and as high quality
> as possible (hopfully running arounf 15-25+)

This is all very well if say you are an animator and want to commit
your work to cdrom to replay it from there, but in the case of making
intro anims for games, for example, it isn't so feasible to pick and
choose the cd-rom speed. It is possible to alter the throughput levels
when making an mpeg file, and we should note that mpeg was originally
designed to run off a 2xspeed cdrom i think so a system that was based
on 4 or 8 speed wouldn't need such heavy compression.

I'm quite interested in a nice new no-loss `read only' anim format (ie
you use some program to generate it then you play it back, not like
with deluxe paint editing, or you convert a different format like
anim5/7 into it). no-loss 16-bit might be quite nice. I'm personally
not so keen for it to necessarily have sound but am keeping that in
mind but it will probably need compressing and certainly mpega is too
slow.

-- 
Paul.

