@NODE "Mail_136" "Re: SV: animation"
 for scott@online.u-net.com; Tue, 6 Apr 1999 19:42:31 +0100
From: "Evan Tuer" <et@enterprise.net>
Organization: !
Date: 6 Apr 99 19:39:34 +0100
Subject: Re: SV: animation
Encoding: 7bit

On 6 Apr 99 17:29:15 +0000, Paul wrote:

> This is all very well if say you are an animator and want to commit
> your work to cdrom to replay it from there, but in the case of making
> intro anims for games, for example, it isn't so feasible to pick and
> choose the cd-rom speed. It is possible to alter the throughput levels
> when making an mpeg file, and we should note that mpeg was originally
> designed to run off a 2xspeed cdrom i think so a system that was based
> on 4 or 8 speed wouldn't need such heavy compression.

4x CD gets you 600k / second sustained, according to sysinfo. 
Personally I don't think you should make the minimum any more than
1 meg per second, because that's going to be reaching the point where
a lot of people's SCSI interfaces or processors run out of steam.

Are you sure that mpeg is definitely too processor intensive?  If
it needs an 030/50 processor minimum, is that too much to ask?  Also,
there's tools available to easily make mpeg files..  All we need is a
decent player that also supports sound (mpegs have sound, don't they?)

By the way, does anyone have an Iomega Buz device?  They look cool,
and it seems to be an external SCSI video grabber, with a hardware
"motion jpeg" encoder: 768x576, 25 frames a second capture and
playback in 24 bit colour with 44 khz stereo audio!  I want..

Another suggestion:  What does Sony Playstation use?  You get some
very good intros on those, though admittedly in low res, it does play
off a 2x cd with very good sound at the same time.  Actually, I should
know what they use, because I have a player in Blitz for them :)

OR

If you're going to make a new lossless format, what are the chances
of making it scalable, so it plays back at the best quality and speed
that your hardware can manage..?  That way, everyone's happy.

You could encode your animation in the best possible resolution if you
were making a game intro and there was plenty of space on the CD, or
if you were sending a little anim by email, you would restrict the
maximum to a sensible file size.
  
  So for example if the maximum needs say 3 meg per second from the
CD, and the CD can only read 1.2 meg sustained, the player just has to
"skip" at the point where the limit is reached in each frame, instead
of reading the rest of the refining data for that frame.

See what I mean?  Is that stupid?


