@NODE "Mail_139" "Re: animation"
 for scott@online.u-net.com; Wed, 7 Apr 1999 00:43:17 +0000
From: Anton Reinauer <anton@ww.co.nz>
Date: Wed, 07 Apr 1999 12:43:26 +1200
Subject: Re: animation

On 06-Apr-99, Paul wrote:
 
> Animation formats such as mpeg have a key frame method whereby the
> compression of subsequent frames is based on a key frame. The problem
> is that this leads to increasing numbers of errors as the frames tick
> over, which is why there are many key frames within a file. 

  What I've always thought would be a good idea; would be, if before
encoding it, you could look through your anim and manually put in the
keyframes yourself- so when the shot changed you could add a keyframe,
maybe add a couple across a Pan etc. As we're only doing intro anims
here and not full length movies, it wouldn't be too much work. This
would help keep the file size and bandwidth down.
  Then maybe your encoder could put in extra keyframes if you stuffed
up. :-) 


-- 
        Anton Reinauer <anton@ww.co.nz>
      


