@NODE "Mail_140" "Re: SV: animation"
 for scott@online.u-net.com; Wed, 7 Apr 1999 04:30:16 +0100
From: "Dave" <dave@nbsamiga.demon.co.uk>
Subject: Re: SV: animation
Date: Wed, 7 Apr 1999 03:02:04 +0100
	charset="iso-8859-1"
Encoding: 7bit


Hi,


>>   So for example if the maximum needs say 3 meg per second from the
>> CD, and the CD can only read 1.2 meg sustained, the player just has to
>> "skip" at the point where the limit is reached in each frame, instead
>> of reading the rest of the refining data for that frame.
>>
>> See what I mean?  Is that stupid?
>
>I dont see how you can skip deltas and still maintain image integrity.
>That's why you have to have key frames, but then the key frames have
>to be predefined in the data so you don't have a very flexible ability
>to skip them when you want.


Well, not stupid ;)...I probably didn`t explain what I meant...my idea was
to fix your video to a fps. I choose 15fps, but you could easily use 30fps
(well, I assume you could...and paul`s right..I probably mean
16fps!)...anyway, what I do is break the animation (video frame cells) into
15`s so I have lots of seperate 1 seconds worth of video (at 320x240*256).
Then I take an iff sound sample, and break that up into 1 second clips (this
gives me say, 44k of 8 bit stereo at 22khz).

So in each chunk of my video file I have (and I`ll try and explain it better
this time ;)

44k sound clip (or 22k if using delta..but the first byte would have to be
normal, in order to skip sound correctly)

75k key frame

These are always the first two things in my 1 second chunk. This always
means that I can start at any one second bit of the video (ie, for a slider
in a video player, or to jump things you`d have an accuracy of 1 second).

Now I need to store another 14 frames of data...and I can use various
methods for each frame. This is where the compression/size problems start.

I imaged that, you could save updated bits, ie, just parts of the last frame
that changed (lines that have changed, boxes of the frame that have changed
and indiviual pixels [in short runs of rows])...all of these frames could
take anywhere from 1 byte to 75k. You could also store a delta if you
couldn`t compress it any other way (ie, you`d compress it with the 3
previous methods, and if it was bigger than using a delta frame, you`d try
using a delta, and if the delta failed, you`d have to store a key frame).

You could also store palette changes (768 bytes I think) which may help the
changes to be smaller (ie, the video image getting lighter/darker or
changing completely).

You could make worse quality videos when encoding by selecting tolereance
values for more lossy video, or have a force use delta compression, which
would sort of give you a maximum size for each 1 second block, but low
quality, but maybe that could be used to generate a low quality movie to
play on low spec machines.

The problems come when you have too many key frames in a one second block.
That would push us well outside of our limits, although it`d take less time
to decode, but the read would take longer.

As it stands, the maximum for my one second video/sound clip would be 1.2mb
/ second (at 15fps with no compression)...it is unlikely that it would ever
need to store that many keyframes in one second...so I`d expect the size to
be a lot smaller (less than half, but that`s still 600k/second). We should
probably aim for 30fps...as that is more reasonable (ie, vhs pal video tapes
run at 25?? or something like that....and that isn`t great), but that make
us need twice as many frames (but I *think* you`d get slightly better
compression, as the frame differences would be less than the same 1 second
slice of video at 15fps??). But it would still take more space I imagine.

I`m glad that a lot of people are taking an interest and coming up with
ideas. There is a lot of things to consider..and it`s easy to miss things.
Using my example, you`d have to be clever when your showing the second of
video...as you really shouldn`t skip 15 frames at the end because it`s a
30fps video running at 15fps, you`d really need to check as you decode..and
then say, decode the next frame..but never give it to the display (ie, no
c2p/wpa8) and just move to the next frame...you`d just need to keep count on
how many ticks you`ve lost (or something like that, but it`s quite
complicated). Other things to consider are that you`d have to do this per
udpate:

Before any updates, you would have to cleverly uncompress the sound for the
whole next one second clip...you may have to do this spliced into the main
udpate loop...I`m not sure how long it`d take to do in one go...(maybe
should specify no sound compression, as sound will only take up a little
bit...but at 44khz 16 bit stereo [future maximum] that`d be a lot of your
read time I suppose, which you could halve with delta compression!) And you
have to get it into chip...but don`t forget the first video frame needs no
decode...simply copy it to video ram..so you have a little free time there.

 Read a chunk of the NEXT one second block from the file (chunksize/number
of frames we have to decode for the current 1 second clip....of course it`s
not as easy as that...this could eat all your time if your not
carefull...though I *think* you can use something like DOIO, to let the
device read the data into ram...but I have a horrible feeling that it could
only read into chip...I`m not sure if it can read into memory while your
using the cpu....either way...it`d need some experimentation to work out
actually how much data you can read from a device while doing other tasks.)

 Decode the next frame from current 1 second video clip (you would repeat
this step and the step above if you are losing time, the actual decode time
of a frame shouldn`t be that bad, as it will should be in fastram and at
worse, you`d have to un delta the current frame..any chance of a speed test
someone??)

 Copy the clip from fastram to hidden video double buffer (aga would use
c2p)

I think this is where my 15fps for 030/50 comes from....ie, to get higher
you`d have to drop the res or raise the read speed and cpu speed. 15fps is
just a guess..(It probably should be 16 fps as paul said).

Non of this probably makes sense....but it was my plan a while back...for an
intro to stick on my game...I wasn`t really out to invent a mpeg
beater..just something I could watch without thinking of my C= 64 ;).

Dave

P.s. I suppose, seeing how my game needs 030+ and fastram, that I shouldn`t
worry about 2 speed cd roms really....maybe I`ll just have a 160x120 lowres
video on there just for them...and make a special border around it on the
play back screen...saying...GET A 4 SPEED CD ROM a thousand times :)




