@NODE "Mail_143" "Re: SV: animation"
 for scott@online.u-net.com; Wed, 7 Apr 1999 18:46:29 +0100
From: "Evan Tuer" <et@enterprise.net>
Organization: !
Date: 7 Apr 99 17:45:49 +0100
Subject: Re: SV: animation
X-Face: D&,gZdIir#^@6X|5{(WImHr@,h+VPcoM%d0.PNs+A\p<X|jwgS^f*Nq1Uak8i1*nMw~]v|f{wq5Ej1jn-7lk~9uN.N|O<,k@vxNgOy`P/^(">BF.d`9TrDMC;)9KWv[pmepq3%EY}EEfVKQ&7c&`F9b/:~Qq1Mt6.W^?\R$H^fg!ouPx.RZs!SW#(g.{]7FjW46K~E*#\OMCI;1ja1fC~r);"<Ub91{Et*0a"g\'klu}pfQfw$c*0]z8v?\2X>6
Encoding: 7bit

On 6 Apr 99 20:59:48 +0000, Paul wrote:
> >   So for example if the maximum needs say 3 meg per second from the
> > CD, and the CD can only read 1.2 meg sustained, the player just has to
> > "skip" at the point where the limit is reached in each frame, instead
> > of reading the rest of the refining data for that frame.
> >
> > See what I mean?  Is that stupid?
>
> I dont see how you can skip deltas and still maintain image integrity.
> That's why you have to have key frames, but then the key frames have
> to be predefined in the data so you don't have a very flexible ability
> to skip them when you want.

I'm thinking of sort of multi layer delta frames.  Umm..  If the first
"layer" contains deltas of a large block size, and the next layer
contains refinements to /that/ layer, but with a smaller block size,
and so on:  When you replay, and you want to stick to a fast
framerate, the player just collects as many layers as it can before
the frame is due do be drawn.  So if there's only time (given the
speed of the CD drive and processor) to get and collate the first
layer of delta onto the keyframe, then the film will look low-res and
blocky, or the film will be replayed in a smaller window
automatically, to compensate.  If it manages three and a half layers,
it'll be better.

So, the keyframes would also be in the lowest, blockiest
format..  I think..  The layers of deltas keep it up to full
resolution if there is enough time, or if there is little enough
difference between frames, or perhaps if you drop half the frames as
per Dave's plan, like from 30 to 15.

[BLOCK1-------------------------------------------->
[audio ,kddddd,dddddd,dddddd,dddddd,kddddd,kddddd,...
 (8)(6) frame1,frame2,frame3,...           ^^^
    skp>  skip>  skip>   (if required)     ||`delta layer 2
                                           |`delta layer 1
                                           `keyframe

Obviously the "block" is not loaded in all at once, that would defeat
the purpose - it's just a one second chunk that can be indexed.

 I know that sounds like an insane amount of "frames" - i.e. like
you've got 10 copies of each delta frame?  But it should work out that
each layer has less information than the last, and that the total data
and filesize is still less than the original "seperate image for each
frame" format, because you're still doing it by delta.  And that
you're not actually drawing 10 times as much, it's just being added to
the screen buffer while it's waiting..

And you could still play it on an 020 with 2x cd drive at full frame
rate, without having seperate files.. hopefully :)

I don't know about sound, but look at Dave's message; you would have
to do something less cool though, like jam 8 bits * 1 second * 22khz
worth of stereo sound sample in with the first frame of each block.. I
don't think you could switch "resolutions" on the fly in the same way
as you could with the graphics, because it would be too noticable, as
it doesn't depend on the sound itself.. You could always put another 6
or 8 bits of sound on just in case though, and the player can skip it if it
isn't going to be able to cope, or it could switch down to mono if the cd
drive is REALLY slow.

Thinking about it, the goal is to make sure the animation plays at the
speed it is meant to - without skipping whole frames at random and
making it all jumpy (like Quicktime and Mpeg do) - or worse just
slowing down without compensation, like AVI does sometimes, and like
IFF presumeably does.

We have to be careful of the filesize though.  If we can get a
good anim into 600k/second, that's fine, but it's still only
15 minutes per CD, which is a scary way of looking at it, but the best
we can do without lossy compression.

No, it /was/ stupid.. Oh well :)


