@NODE "Mail_144" "Re: SV: animation"
 for scott@online.u-net.com; Wed, 7 Apr 1999 22:36:08 +0100
From: "Paul" <paulwest@stationone.demon.co.uk>
Organization: private
Date: 7 Apr 99 19:09:49 +0000
Subject: Re: SV: animation
Encoding: 7bit

Evan Tuer,

> We have to be careful of the filesize though.  If we can get a
> good anim into 600k/second, that's fine, but it's still only
> 15 minutes per CD, which is a scary way of looking at it, but the best
> we can do without lossy compression.
> 
> No, it /was/ stupid.. Oh well :)

Hmm.. well seems a nice sort of approach,a bit like the progressive
effect of gif and png, whereby you could produce a large blocky
display from the first batch of pixels and then gradually refine it
smaller and smaller if there is enough cpu time. Thing is that it
would like a bit shite unless you were actually quite close to the
full complement of pixels and even then, all of these layers of data
are going to make for larger files.

Anyway, i don't think it will be necessary to have the animation
slowing down if it can be run at fullspeed on a target minimum setup.
I suppose there is that you can have a lower quality playback if you
haven't got the beef to see it in full, but if you want quality loss
then you might as well go for a lossy format and be done with it?

-- 
Paul.

