@NODE "Mail_146" "Re: SV: animation"
 for scott@online.u-net.com; Thu, 8 Apr 1999 01:11:30 +0000
From: "Dave" <dave@nbsamiga.demon.co.uk>
Subject: Re: SV: animation
Date: Thu, 8 Apr 1999 01:48:28 +0100
	charset="iso-8859-1"
Encoding: 7bit



>On 7 Apr 99 19:09:49 +0000, Paul wrote:
>
>> Anyway, i don't think it will be necessary to have the animation
>> slowing down if it can be run at fullspeed on a target minimum setup.
>> I suppose there is that you can have a lower quality playback if you
>> haven't got the beef to see it in full, but if you want quality loss
>> then you might as well go for a lossy format and be done with it?
>
>Well not so much that, it was more so that people with faster
>computers could get the advantage of a better picture.  Then you don't
>have to decide so critically what the format is, and its more
>flexible.  We would have to try it to know if the filesize was going
>to be much bigger.. of course it would be bigger if the maximum was
>set to a bigger size, but then, if it's a CD game, who cares?


Hmm...well you could simply set the specification of a new format to, say
640x480@256 with 16 bit stereo @ 44khz running at 25 fps...that`d be about
7.6 mb/sec. Then you`d need a compression ratio of 10:1 (pretty tricky and
probably very lossy) to make any use of that with maybe an eight speed cd
rom (I doubt you could read it at 25fps with a quad speed). And a CD would
only store 16 minutes of video. I personally I need something that
works..something I can make a 3/4 minute intro for my game that won`t be too
big, so I can use the rest of the cd for lots of game maps and maybe real
audio tracks....and an ending movie! I`m not out to make a new video cd
format that runs on the amiga....I think that would be pointless..you`d be
better off spending your time getting a decent mpeg decoder running faster
(unless you already have a very fast cpu and graphics card), and then you
can watch video cd`s to your hearts content :).

Dave



