@NODE "Mail_157" "Re: Animation Format's"
 for scott@online.u-net.com; Thu, 1 Apr 1999 20:45:56 +0100
From: "Paul" <paulwest@stationone.demon.co.uk>
Organization: private
Date: 1 Apr 99 20:02:50 +0000
Subject: Re: Animation Format's
Encoding: 7bit

Anim format dudes,

> There is already a format, I think it's called Wildfire or something
> like that.. There was a demo of a huge rendered film, with a good
> soundtrack on the CUCD over a year ago, it was very impressive and ran
> on my (at the time) slow machine at very fast framerate and
> resolution.

You mean yafa? I think wildfire is the actual animation software not
the animation data format.

As far as designing a new anim format goes though there are three main
areas...a) getting and outputting the sound, getting and outputting
the graphics, and making sure they are synchronised. If we're talking
16-bit sound then some sort of compression will be necessary which
could get pretty nasty unless some external tool is used. Personally I
still think that normal 8-bit modules (octamed, etc) suffice and are
easier to synchronise to. The anim format itself would presumably have
to either have some fast decompression method or be loaded into ram in
bulk and played back. This is why the iff anim format has different
variants, some are better at compression but slower to play,and others
like anim8_32 are fast to play but take up lots of ram. The fastest
method of course is a dump of raw uncompressed data in a solid block
but then it wouldn't exactly be an animation format so we'd at least
need to look into delta frames (differences since the last frame).
Doublebuffering is not a problem as it is with direct-to-chipram
formats because you can double or triplebuffer the output with no
extra hassles. It should be possible to had a 320x240 anim playing at
25fps on 030/50 and upwards wether it's full screen changes or only
smaller parts.But then the sound has to be considered...

any ideas?

-- 
Paul.

IRC: #amiga, Dalnet: #blitz
WWW: http://www.stationone.demon.co.uk
E-M: paul@stationone.demon.co.uk


