@NODE "Mail_160" "Re: Animation Format's"
 for scott@online.u-net.com; Fri, 2 Apr 1999 01:48:07 +0100
Date: Fri, 02 Apr 1999 01:40:58 +0100
From: Paul Burkey <burkey@bigfoot.com>
X-Accept-Language: en
Subject: Re: Animation Format's
Encoding: 7bit

Evan Tuer wrote:
> > extra hassles. It should be possible to had a 320x240 anim playing at
> > 25fps on 030/50 and upwards wether it's full screen changes or only
> > smaller parts.But then the sound has to be considered...
> 
> I think you covered all the points :)  But the question is, should we
> not be looking at a more scalable or high-end format: there's not much
> point to make another 320x240 anim format, with sound or without.

I used my own custom anim format in Foundation and I found it hard
push the anim beyond the 'poor quality 320x200 "lossy" and slow'
clasification. I have to say that my anim playback routine is far
from optimized but I knew that there wasn`t much more I could do
to make it run at 25fps without using very heavy compression.

My anim was 10meg in medium quality (a very 'lossy' mode) and 17Meg
in high quality. The high quality anim was 17Meg which gave me
almost 22k per frame. Now 22K per frame isn`t much and if you`re
trying to run at 25frames per second you`ve got yourself 500k
of data per second to parse. 500k per second isn`t too much but
that is only a 320x200 anim with some quality loss and no sound
(I used a module for sound).

> Does anyone know more about Yafa?  Perhaps we should try adopting
> that, or AVI, or do some clever shortcut decoding of mpeg which would
> work on slower machines?

The most common anim formats are Mpeg, AVI and QT/MOV. These are
widely used because they use very heavy compression. Such compression
at high speed is not really possible on an 030/50. So you either end
up with a format that is too bulky to work with or a complex
compression system that takes too much power to decompress. 

Cheers,

Paul

-- 
< Paul Burkey http://www.sneech.freeserve.co.uk >


