@NODE "Mail_161" "Re: Animation Format's"
 for scott@online.u-net.com; Sat, 3 Apr 1999 00:27:05 +0000
From: "Dave" <dave@nbsamiga.demon.co.uk>
Subject: Re: Animation Format's
Date: Sat, 3 Apr 1999 01:29:20 +0100
	charset="iso-8859-1"
Encoding: 7bit

Hi,

 I`ve been following this thread with some interest. I think your thinking
more of a Video Format, rather than an animation format, one that looks like
your watching a video. Also, I`m not sure where your getting your specs
from....very few of the avi`s I`ve seen get much above 15fps, never mind
25fps...and they are usually of small size (160x120 for 25fps or maybe
320x240 for 15fps)..I have two on my pc, a 2 second avi with no sound which
is 160x120 and is 156k, and a 7 minutes 23 seconds video, which is 320x240
with sound which is 126mb. When I convert this to an mpg it still takes
76mb, but looks a lot worse..especially when full screen. There is no magic
answer...all we really need is something that`s usable on the amiga. It
doesn`t have to be compatible with anything else. The other thing is the
read speed of the device (ie, a 2 speed cdrom as on the cd32...correct??
will only pump 300k per second out...hd`s should be much better....anyone up
on the average speed of amiga hd`s??).

Sound could be easily added...all you need to do is split all the frames up
into seconds. Then store a one second sound clip at the start of all the
frames for a second (which you decode first) and then your sound will always
run at the right speed (ie...no gaps, and no jumps), and you simply jog the
video to fit it...(ie, if your fps for the video is 15 fps and your
currently running at 7fps...you need to skip every other frame..or you may
be running at 30fps, which means you need to stay with odd frames an extra
tick).

 Be aware that Avi and Quicktime are both just storage containers, to
describe a video. They are not compression types...you use different
compression methods inside them (same as microidiots ASF). I think the new
quicktime format is used on dvd`s??? I`m not sure about that, but I have got
some manga video disc`s and they are simply mpeg`s (ie...500mb+ mpeg for 1
hour of video+sound probably at 320x240 and 30fps). So as you can
see...there is no magic answer for a video format...otherwise we`d see it on
pc`s...mpeg is the best (well..actually I prefer bintel`s indeo...as it
looks better when you view it full screen) for compression but it takes a
lot of processing power, and looks pretty bad!

Just some thoughts ;),

Dave


P.s. I did work on a video format AGES ago...but I got VERY VERY bored. It`s
easy to write code to decode a simple video format, but actually making
tools to convert from another format (like AVI!!) is a incredibly boring and
long process...one which I could never be bothered to start. It might be
better to use chunky fastmem bitmaps and c2p to chip for aga...but then
don`t hope for greater than 15 fps....



