P.s. this is what gets me...

Taken from               MPEG-2 Encoder / Decoder, Version 1.2, July 19,
1996

The primary application targeted during the MPEG-2 definition process
was the all-digital transmission of interlaced broadcast TV quality
video at coded bitrates between 4 and 9 Mbit/sec.  However, the MPEG-2
syntax has been found to be efficient for other applications such as
those at higher bit rates and sample rates (e.g. HDTV).

Surely this means that they aimed for broadcast tv quality (interlaced??),
and then later found it was good at compressing higher quality, but surely
this depends on the quality of the video you start with before the
compression?? ie, you`d need a better source, and you`d get less
compression, but it`d still be in their ratio for good compression, but it
would be outputting at a better res/frequency??


