@NODE "Mail_189" "Animation Formats"
 for scott@online.u-net.com; Tue, 6 Apr 1999 23:22:32 +0000
From: Jamie Bentley <sniper@technet2000.com.au>
Date: Tue, 03 Jan 1978 16:27:31 +0500
Organization: Sniper Productions
Subject: Animation Formats

 Heya,

 There's been a lot of debate (50+ mails) about the best anim format.
Obviously if you want support on other formats, nothing beats MPG, QT or AVI.

 The problem is even on an 060 none (except perhaps AVI) of the above formats
is really worth while (mainly due to the  amount of time needed to convert),
but for raw speed an Anim8w IFF file is excellent. They play at 25fps full
screen (lowres) when every frame has the same palette, and they're still quite
good even when every frame has a different palette.

 Unfortunatly, they have almost no compression, but when you compress them
with Powerpacker or lha  (or any decent compression method) they go down quite
well. Obviously realtime decompression is a waste of processor time (thus
Anim5 is useless).

 If your using a fairly decent graphics card a MPG file might be the best
option, because if you customize the format (remove ALL error checking and
remove all the non-essentials) it would work fine. Obviously, to go with this
you'd also need to make a fool-proof (100% working) conversion program so you
can make the anims with NO errors so when you play it out again it plays as
fast as possible (like the XING Mpeg format).

 Shortcuts might need to be taken, like storing palettes in the actual format
etc.

 Anyway, thats my perspective on things :)

 JB


