@NODE "Mail_192" "animation formats"
 for scott@online.u-net.com; Sun, 18 Apr 1999 23:25:42 +0000
From: "Paul" <paulwest@stationone.demon.co.uk>
Organization: private
Date: 18 Apr 99 23:24:35 +0000
Subject: animation formats
Encoding: 7bit

Hi folks,

I have continued to dabble with anim compression. My method was to
interleave 16 frames together and do combinations of byterun,
repetition, bytesequences and rubthrough operations. Well, so far it's
not doing too bad. From what I can tell, it mostly gives better
compression than gif png iff and archived (lha/lzx) raw, for a given
image.

However, I found that if i left out the repetition compression, which
is similar to LZ77 sliding-window compression, and then running the
larger output file through something like lha, it gets an even smaller
filesize.

It looks as though a simple combination of byterun/bytesequence and
rubthrough/skip, as a `pre-compression', should be used in combination
with a decent string compression such as the suggest xpk nuke. This
produces superior file sizes compared to just compressing raw frames
because the frame can be somewhat reduced by the fact that not all of
it has changed since the previous one.

With this in mind, might i refer you to the YAFA format. It is
basically an iff anim7 format, with the exception that the delta data
is further compressed by running it through an xpk routine. So it
looks like the people who designed it came to the same conclusion.

I dont know if YAFA can be played from disk or not, or what xpk it
uses (it may not be a fast one).

I have converted some of my animation effort into asm, but have been
reluctant to spend the time on converting the repetition string
routine until having discovering these issues of size.

What I will try and do now is simply a format similar to anim7,
doing basic compression to represent the frames in their delta format,
and to then apply something else to the resulting codes such as xpk
nuke. At this time I cant think of any other ways of improving
lossless compression without causing massive slowdown - such as the
filters of the png format.

-- 
Paul.

IRC: #amiga, Dalnet: #blitz
WWW: http://www.stationone.demon.co.uk
E-M: paul@stationone.demon.co.uk


