@NODE "Mail_195" "animations"
 for scott@online.u-net.com; Wed, 21 Apr 1999 16:49:55 +0100
From: "Paul" <paulwest@stationone.demon.co.uk>
Organization: private
Date: 21 Apr 99 16:41:33 +0000
Subject: animations
Encoding: 7bit

Hiya,

I've pretty much finished trying to compress animations now. The best
compression I've got so far is to chop up the anim into sets of 16
frames, interleave them together and then compress with something like
xpk NUKE, RAKE or GZIP. It gives quite good filesizes considering. At
worst the ratio is about 1:2 and at best it may be 1:80 (for a
cartoony thing). However, the problem is decompression speed. On my
040/25 it is taking between 1 and 2 seconds to decompress the data
back to raw, which is about 1.3 megs for 320x256. At best this would
mean it took a second just to decompress 16 frames, so would only play
at a maximum of 16fps, and that doesn't include time to convert c2p or
to sort out the asynchronous cdrom loading or whatever. Thats the low
end of the scale for the most primitive of anims. At the top end a
frame rate of 8-12fps looks like the maximum, on my cpu anyway. I
dunno about you but these framerates are a little too low to really be
pleasing to look at. The only way around that would be to have a
smaller frame size. 320x200 may get you to an average of 12fps on
040/25 or perhaps something like 320x176 or 256x176 would get you up
to 16fps. Of course if you have an 060 then the sun can come out to
play, but this leaves 030 and 040 owners in the lurch.

The alternative as fred suggests of loading in raw data, would require
a 6xspeed cdrom for 320x200 (about 60k per frame amounts to 1.6megs at
25fps). On a gfx-card it could be spooled direct to video ram or
perhaps have a seperate planar version to do the same on AGA. I
personally have a 6xspeed but I figure it more likely people would
have 4 or 8, and a 4xspeed wouldn't be fast enough for 16fps at
320x200. All this doesn't include sound either.

If everyone had an 060 and a 4xspeed cdrom it wouldn't be much trouble
to get 320x240 at 16fps or a slightly smaller size at 25fps. It isn't
too much the filesize that's a problem. The worse anim I managed
compressed a single frame from 80k down to 45k on average for 320x256
so a 4xspeed may be just fast enough to spool 16 320x200 frames in a
second for really busy anims. It's quite demanding but let us not
forget there is no quality loss (except that 24-bit to 256-colours is
lossy). Most of the anim's I've got have fairly still backgrounds with
something large moving and tend to get down to between 12-25k per
frame which for a 4xspeed cdrom would allow just about 25fps, *IF* the
decompression were fast enough, and at the moment it seems to take
about a second to decompress 16 fairly avereage anim frames on an
040/25. If all this lark was going on asynchronously you might get
16fps performance from a 4xspeed cdrom with an 040/25, for fairly
compressible anims. The cdrom bottleneck depends on how compressible
the anim is, and the decompression bottleneck depends on the cpu and
filesize. I don't think you'd be able to get up to a decent speed with
an 030/50.

Hmm, well, i suppose it also depends what size anim frames you want.
320x240 would be nice. I did try a rather compressible anim that is a
sort of diagrammatical representation of the path of a comet as
plotted by some astrology program. It compresses very heavily down to
something like 70k for 16 frames, and is 640x512 frame size. But then
that's getting past 5 megs of raw data which for me takes about 9
seconds to decompress, and I don't imagine 2fps playback to be very
entertaining. On the other hand, a smaller framesize could really help
matters. 320x200 would surely be acceptable and many would be plenty
happy to see some nice quarterscreen anim or 3/4 screen perhaps, like
256x176 or something, or halfscreen. For decent cpu performance you
really have to consider the size of the screen cus it amounts to how
much raw data has to be output and that is quite a deciding factor.
640x320 is going to need to be streamed raw from a 12xspeed cdrom
using an 060 in order to play at 16fps, for example.

The other question is how much of a market there is for such software.
Some people just want to play their own anims, others want to make
game intros. And after you've rendered your nice raytraced
extravaganza you don't wanna find out that it will only playback
decent for most people with a real small screen.

<shrugs>

Does anyone know how to do asynchronous i/o then? We might as well
give it a bit of a go and see what sort of results we can get. We need
to read in a chunk of data containing 16 compressed frames from the
cdrom. Then a loop can begin to asynchronously read the next 16 frame
chunk while at the same time decompressing the previous 16 frame
chunk. After the 32nd frame has been read in I think then you can
start to display the decompressed frames. It's not exactly feasible to
have a `16-buffered' screen although, mind you, that would fit well
inside 2 megs for lores allowing you to start displaying shortly after
starting the decompression.

Or does anyone think it's not worth bothering cus the playback
speed/size is too naff?

 --  .Paul.

