@NODE "Mail_197" "Re: animations"
 for scott@online.u-net.com; Wed, 21 Apr 1999 21:29:14 +0100
Date: Wed, 21 Apr 1999 20:33:25 +0100
From: Paul Burkey <burkey@bigfoot.com>
X-Accept-Language: en
Subject: Re: animations
Encoding: 7bit

Paul wrote:
> I've pretty much finished trying to compress animations now. The best
> compression I've got so far is to chop up the anim into sets of 16
> frames, interleave them together and then compress with something like
> xpk NUKE, RAKE or GZIP.

The compression I was using was based on IMPL (LZ77) and I notice
that NUKE beats it on speed and compression ratios so you`re probably
on the right track here although I read some stats that said IMPL
can unpack at about 360K/s but that was on an 030/25 which is really
well below any current specs.

> The alternative as fred suggests of loading in raw data, would
> require a 6xspeed cdrom for 320x200 (about 60k per frame amounts
> to 1.6megs at 25fps). On a gfx-card it could be spooled direct to
> video ram or perhaps have a seperate planar version to do the
> same on AGA.

ooh, I wouldn`t try that. I'd forget about the speed of CD's for
the current moment because those 300k/s 600k/s speeds never really
bare any relation to the actual real world speeds you get and the
speed seems to drop further as the file size grows. This is why
I suggest the asynchronous i/o is an important factor.

> Does anyone know how to do asynchronous i/o then? We might as well
> give it a bit of a go and see what sort of results we can get.

The obvious answer is the AsyncIO.library but after trying to
figure it out for a few days I gave up :) The other idea is
to launch an external program which can communicate with your
main task and act as a server for the compressed buffers. The
external task can load the data and then provide your main task
with a "data ready, here it is" message and then it would sit
and wait for the main task to acnowlege it. At that point the
external task would work on the second batch of data and build
that up in a second buffer. So, as the main task is unpacking
and displaying buffer 1, the external task is preparing buffer 2
and so on. This sounds like a crazy idea but it works in a
similar way to a TCP client/server project I did last year. I
might have a go at implimenting this idea in such a way as
it can be used in various applications where an external task
can feed the main task some information. Most of the work is
already done in my TCP Chat server.

Cheers,

Paul

-- 
< Paul Burkey http://www.sneech.freeserve.co.uk >


