Hi,

>ooh, I wouldn`t try that. I'd forget about the speed of CD's for
>the current moment because those 300k/s 600k/s speeds never really
>bare any relation to the actual real world speeds you get and the
>speed seems to drop further as the file size grows. This is why
>I suggest the asynchronous i/o is an important factor.
>
>> Does anyone know how to do asynchronous i/o then? We might as well
>> give it a bit of a go and see what sort of results we can get.
>


Hmmm..well in the days of the A500, you could have a 320x256x32 screen, 8
16x16 sprites (well more like 7), all 4 sound channels going, the blitter
blitting some stuff, and the disk reading into ram....while still processing
instructions with the cpu. The reason why the 68000 is slow (well, more like
the reason chipmem is slow) is all down to dma...what made the a500 a kick
ass machine at the time...now holds us up, when we need to do cpu intentsive
tasks (not using 030+ into fastram on an a1200.....though).....

You could try and emulate asynchronous i/o, by using another task to keep
filling the next buffer, but this would require cpu time, and in my opinion
wouldn`t be any better than reading it frame by frame and decoding. The only
other way to read it in is to read it into chipmem, but then there are a lot
of other problems, and you would lose a lot of decode speed. (well, you`d
lose decode speed if you were on a machine with fastram). As far as I
understand, DMA can`t access fastram (ie, no sprites, blits, sound screens,
or direct disk data in fastram). Maybe you could write some code to read it
into chip with dma, then transfer it into fast...but I doubt you`d gain much
by doing that....(ie, you`d wait for it to read into chip, then copy it from
chip>fast, decode it, then send it back to chip maybe with c2p)...and we all
know that chipram is slowwwwwwww.....

Sorry that doesn`t help :(,

Dave



