@NODE "Mail_205" "Re: animations"
 for scott@online.u-net.com; Tue, 27 Apr 1999 05:37:09 +0100
From: "Dave" <dave@nbsamiga.demon.co.uk>
Subject: Re: animations
Date: Tue, 27 Apr 1999 05:35:25 +0100
	charset="iso-8859-1"
Encoding: 7bit


>>> I made a test program with normal OS calls and another with
>>> asyncio.library calls, and I got almost exactly the same results,
>>> ie. time taken to read large files...
>
>> The point is to tell asynchio to read data into a buffer while you are
>> processing some other data.  Isn't there some documentation for it
>
>Well, maybe I should have another look, but I thought I'd tried
>everything...
>


I wouldn`t bother...with asyncio, you first need a buffer that is the size
of the amount of data you need to read to in one pass, otherwise the the
read call will hold it up readsize/(buffersize/2) times the speed of which
it reads buffersize/2 in. What happens is that it uses 2 buffers, so that it
can copy memory the other buffer, while it is reading in the next buffer.
The problem is that it is having to copymem the data from it`s buffer to
your own, instead of doing a direct read to your buffer. I would imagen that
it doesn`t make it any faster, as normally you would just read a lump of
data in one go..ie, using a readmem to a single memory buffer, instead of
trying to read data and do other things at the same time (ie, while you
would continually be reading in the next block, the last block would be
using cpu time to copy to your buffer, therefore you would first have to
wait for the memcopy to finish before you could do any thing with the cpu
yourself).

Dave


