@NODE "Mail_218" "Re: any PC users there?"
 for scott@online.u-net.com; Sun, 18 Apr 1999 16:42:41 +0100
From: "David McMinn" <D.Mcminn@eee.rgu.ac.uk>
Organization: The Robert Gordon University, E&EE
Date: Sun, 18 Apr 1999 16:41:23 +0100
encoding: Quoted-printable
Subject: Re: any PC users there?

> > > shouldn't hide it self. Persional I beleve that PC sould declare the=
m
> > > selves as 070 etc.
> > 
> > Not actually possible seeing as exec.library only provides a single by=
te
> > for the processor, the maximum of which is 060.
> That dosn't make sence, 6 is high's number for a byte.
> 
> Byte is made of 8 Bits which are ever 0 / 1.
> 
> Or its 2by power2by power2by power2by power2by power2by power2by
> power2 which =3D 256.  Or CPU terms is number +/-128.  And you are
> saying 6 is max.  I must be stupied or something.

 Not stupid, but you don't know how the processor number is stored in the =
exec 
base. (James Boyd knows all about this BTW :)

Within your byte, you have 8 bits, as you have already said. Each one of t=
hese 
bits represents a flag for a processor, not the number.

Bit Meaning
0   68010
1   68020
2   68030
3   68040
4   68881
5   68882
6   68040 FPU
7   68060 (was spare)

 All the lower processor flags are set for higher processors, i.e. for a 6=
8040, 
the flags for 040,030,020,010 are all set. Same for FPUs, if you have 6888=
2, 
then flag for 68881 is also set.

 Incidentally, someone (maybe Philips?) already produced a chip called the=
 
68070, but it was just the name that was similar, it was less powerful tha=
n 
68010. That was in an old AF.


|) /\ \/ ][ |)   |\/| =A9 |\/| ][ |\| |\|
 dmcminn@house-of-mojo.freeserve.co.uk
  http://members.xoom.com/David_McMinn
             ICQ=3D16827694
Accept that some days you're the pigeon, and some days you're the statue.


