@NODE "Mail_219" "Re: any PC users there?"
 for scott@online.u-net.com; Sun, 18 Apr 1999 17:14:42 +0100
From: Rick Hodger <rick.thehub@bigfoot.com>
Date: Sun, 18 Apr 1999 10:54:38 +0100
Organization: Pagan Software
Subject: Re: any PC users there?

I watched as Andrew Guard hammered "Re: any PC users there?" out on their
keyboard...

> Well, well Rick Hodger, OK then but...
>> I watched as Andrew Guard hammered "Re: any PC users there?" out on
their
>> keyboard...

>>> This would be intresting information.  I looking at from view point
>>> that system should declare what is because I belive the system
>>> shouldn't hide it self. Persional I beleve that PC sould declare them
>>> selves as 070 etc.

>> Not actually possible seeing as exec.library only provides a single byte
>> for the processor, the maximum of which is 060.
> That dosn't make sence, 6 is high's number for a byte.

> Byte is made of 8 Bits which are ever 0 / 1.

> Or its 2by power2by power2by power2by power2by power2by power2by
> power2 which = 256.  Or CPU terms is number +/-128.  And you are
> saying 6 is max.  I must be stupied or something.

No, cause it doesn't use a scale of one to six.  An 060 is indicated by it
being set to 255.  A full 040 is 127, and so on.  As 255 is the highest it
can go, you couldn't possibly have a 070 without making a new version of
the OS.  All just to accomodate an emulation of the real thing?

-- 
