@NODE "Mail_232" "Audio compression"
 for scott@online.u-net.com; Thu, 15 Apr 1999 23:40:39 +0100
From: Anton Reinauer <anton@ww.co.nz>
Date: Fri, 16 Apr 1999 10:32:37 +1200
Subject: Audio compression

On 16-Apr-99, Dave wrote:
 
> You must have seen a compressed 8svx?? audiomaster writes them when
> you ask it to......Fibonacci compression is the 4 bit delta of a
> single 8 byte sample (ie, you ge 50% compression always). But the
> problem is, it`s not quite the same as normal delta. Basically the
> first byte is a real byte (-128 to +128) and then the next byte is two
> 4 bit deltas. The first delta modifys the first byte, then the second
> modifys the new byte...and you have 3 bytes from 2. The problem is
> with encoding...as you only have 4 bit delta precision...as you
> compress the sample...you may find you reach a lot of points in the
> sample which are way out side the data range...then what happens is
> you need to go back to the start and flatten out the sample..so it`ll
> fit better using delta. This can happen over and over...causing a lot
> of time to be wasted. If you don`t do that...well, I don`t know...it`d
> sound pretty bad I`d guess ;)......there are other sound compression
> routines, and 8svx is VERY old.....but it`s simple and you are always
> getting 50% compression!
 
  Hmm, I see this works if your delta is in range (4 bit +/- 8 ; only
6.25% :-/  - But you don't lose any quality if it is!
  You could use it with the 4 bit encoding mentioned in the other post,
so you're using 2 bit deltas- bizarrely your range jumps up to 25% :-)

-- 
