On 15-Apr-99, Dave wrote:
> Hi Anton,
> 
>> I'm rather interested in this, as later on (much later on ;), I
>> would
>> like to have a look into sound compression for real time multi-player
>> game conversations (as some PC games now have).
>>   Sound is apparently hard to compress there's not much repetition,
>> but they've seemed to have been able to compress it a lot to allow it
>> on LANs and even through the net!
  
> Me and a few friends thought that`d be cool too....we tried it on
> Freespace..and I have to say it sucked...and everything slowed
> down..and you could barely tell 1 player from another....seemed like a
> cool idea at the time...but seeing how we played it over lan (in
> separate rooms to try and make it better) it was hardly spectacular,
> and I would imagine pretty dire over the big I.
 
    Hah, thought that might be the case- just hype! - That's what you
normally get if PC programmers say that they've created some amazing
new software technology. It probably works if you have a 500mhz PIII-
that wasn't actually availiable when the game came out ;-)

   A 1 second sample at 10 khz (good quality for speech) takes 200 bytes
per frame (50th). That would be 3.2k per frame (receiving from 8
players, and sending to 8 players). If the sound compression mentioned
on the list gives adequate quality, then that would drop to 1.6k per
frame (50%). That's 80k per second!
   Now a 28k modem can handle around 3k per second (as I don't think the
modem could compress the sample to any degree), and a 56k would be
around 6k/sec! 
   Hmmmm problem...  :-)  So you're looking at one sound sample being
transmitted at decent quality, maybe two at fairly crappy quality (a
5khz sampling speed).

> P.s. I`m still messing with the game 3d engine...so it`ll be a while
> longer before I patch in the net play routines.

 That's good, hopefully I'll have time to fix up the game interface by
then, so any changes I make later, can be put into your game just by
updating the functions :-) .
 
  Seeya later- Anton

