Hi,

>  Hmm, I see this works if your delta is in range (4 bit +/- 8 ; only
>6.25% :-/  - But you don't lose any quality if it is!
>  You could use it with the 4 bit encoding mentioned in the other post,
>so you're using 2 bit deltas- bizarrely your range jumps up to 25% :-)


Sort of...but see sami`s email...it uses different numbers, so you can get
big differences from those 4 bits...(-128 -64 -32 -16 -8 -4 -2 -1 0 1 2 4 8
16 32 64)...I`d forgotten what the numbers were ;)...been a while since I
used it..but I`m sure I`m correct about you having to go back when you start
having big differences and flatten the sample, because big differences would
compound the error in the delta I think...right sami??? The other
encoding..I assume you mean the video...but in video it works
differently..well how I plan to do it...you decode the frame into 2x2
blocks...ie

11 22 33 44
11 22 33 44
55 66 77 88
55 66 77 88

Then you simply keep the same chroma values for all pixels in the same
square (I`ve not decided wether to use a mean value, or a biased value, or
highest/lowest yet...depends after some testing)....so for the 4 1111
pixels, you have a Y (luminescence....it`s not...but that`s what most ppl
will understand...and if you not it`s not..then you have no need for an
explanation!) for each pixel (4 bytes) and 2 UV values...(2 Bytes).....as
they should be closer. So you`ll similar shades of the same colour in a
single 2x2 block....(ie blurs edges...hence lossy)...this give you better
output to different rgb format in my opinion, instead of fixing it at say,
16 RGB....and then having the same colours, whether viewed under 16/24/32
bit. And still should be workable under 8 bit (though I`m not sure how good
2 bits of blue will be...but we`ll soon see!)....

Dave


