@NODE "Mail_242" "Audio Control"
 for scott@online.u-net.com; Tue, 27 Apr 1999 10:17:45 +0100
X-Originating-IP: [194.18.83.122]
From: "Peter Thor" <peterthor@hotmail.com>
Subject: Audio Control
Date: Tue, 27 Apr 1999 11:16:36 CEST

Hello all ye lads =) Back with a new e-mail for a while.

How would I go telling if there is a program using the audio.device?
I've glanced in the autodocs, but really can't end up with any good 
results
using opendevice().

So, what I did was actually read the 4 first bits from DMACONR 
($DFF002) who
are set accordingly if or not if the corresponding audio channels DMA 
is used. Hard, yes I know, but it's a temporary solution (:

This generates one question (all code regarding this is in 100% 
assembler as a function and is run in Amigamode)
I experienced _some_ unstable results while reading DMACONR by doing 
this, therefor did I nest the read of DMACONR inside a forbid_, 
permit_ loop (however mainly while running other programs, patches 
and so forth =)how legal is this? 
Using forbid_ and permit _ isn't really a nice thing to do, but it 
seemed more stable at tunes.

This might be one way of only telling IF any sound is playing right 
now, but
what I'd like is to have exclusive access of audio.device.

Kind regards, Thor.

<- blitz source code ->

*Description:* Check if Audio DMA is being used during runtime
<sb>
Function.l CheckAudio {  }
  ;
  ; CheckAudio v0.7 by Peter Thor 1999-04-22
  ;
  ; Checks if Audio DMA is occupied - that is some program is playing 
sound in some form
  ;
  ; It loops 4 times, checking every audio dma channel, they might 
not _all_ be used
  ;


  ;clear registers to use- NEVER use  CLR Dn  on 020+ !

  MOVE.l    #0,d0           ;result of DMACONR
  MOVE.l    #0,d1           ;channelcounter
  MOVE.l    #0,d2           ;loopcounter

  LEA.l     $dff002,a0      ;addy of DMACONR
  MOVE.b    1(a0),d0        ;get the lowest byte (%XXXXxxxx) xxxx=4 
audio dma channels

loop:
  CMP.b     #4,d2           ;loopcounter to ensure looping 4 times (4 
audio channel dma's)
  BEQ       finish          ;if looped 4 times, end
  BTST.b    d1,d0           ;d1 - channelcounter for what channel to 
test, not the same as d2!
  BNE       tstnextdma      ;audio dma channel is enabled - eg playing
  ADD       #1,d2           ;if not playing, increase loopcounter
  BRA       loop            ;and loop

tstnextdma:
  ADD       #1,d1           ;increase channelcounter
  ADD       #1,d2           ;increase loopcounter
  BRA       loop            ;and loop

finish:
  CMP       #1,d1
  BGE       noaccess        ;dma audio channel(s) is/are in use - all 
from 1 to all 4
  CMP       #0,d1
  BEQ       audioaccess     ;ALL dma audio channels are free

noaccess:
  MOVE.l    #0,d0           ;can't obtain audio, return false
  AsmExit

audioaccess:
  MOVE.l    #-1,d0          ;can obtain audio, return true
  AsmExit

End Function




