@NODE "Mail_243" "Re: Audio Control"
 for scott@online.u-net.com; Fri, 30 Apr 1999 02:42:00 +0100
From: "Dave" <dave@nbsamiga.demon.co.uk>
Subject: Re: Audio Control
Date: Thu, 29 Apr 1999 20:28:08 +0100
	charset="iso-8859-1"
Encoding: 7bit

>Hello all ye lads =) Back with a new e-mail for a while.


Hi Peter,

>How would I go telling if there is a program using the audio.device?
>I've glanced in the autodocs, but really can't end up with any good
>results
>using opendevice().


The problem with opendevice is that if something else has priority control
over this device, you won`t be given it. This tells you that the device is
in use (or atleast the channels you want are locked out). So then you should
put up a requester informing the user that the audio channels are in use
(like every other bit of software I`ve ever seen does).

>So, what I did was actually read the 4 first bits from DMACONR
>($DFF002) who
>are set accordingly if or not if the corresponding audio channels DMA
>is used. Hard, yes I know, but it's a temporary solution (:


I dont think that will work..image a mod playing, with quiet gaps in the
mod`s for all channels, then your reading would come out zero, even though
something`s busy with the audio device. Plus, maybe another program has just
asked for a stereo pair of audio channels (ie, 0 and 2), which means 1 and 3
would be free (if that`s any used to you).

>This generates one question (all code regarding this is in 100%
>assembler as a function and is run in Amigamode)
>I experienced _some_ unstable results while reading DMACONR by doing
>this, therefor did I nest the read of DMACONR inside a forbid_,
>permit_ loop (however mainly while running other programs, patches
>and so forth =)how legal is this?
>Using forbid_ and permit _ isn't really a nice thing to do, but it
>seemed more stable at tunes.


That is the way to do it..so long as you don`t spend forever in forbid_
permit_ then you should be alright, though if you do that a lot, say 100
times a second, you`ll notice the other programs multitasking would go
jerky. All forbid and permit does is to temporarly disable multitasking,
just stops tasks messing with system while your doing something (hence the
reason you need to do that when processing task searchs). Enable_ and
Disable_ would cause problems if you took longer than a frame, as they
disable interrupts too.

>This might be one way of only telling IF any sound is playing right
>now, but
>what I'd like is to have exclusive access of audio.device.


What you need to do is open the audio device with a priority of -127. This
means you want exclusive access to the channel combination(s) you specified.
If you can`t get a lock on these channels, you won`t get the device, so then
you need to warn the user to kill his mod player ;)....


Hope that helps,

Dave

P.s. If you need any help with the audio device...I`m just about to do
double buffer sound using the audio device with blitz...so I will have some
source that might help you ;)



