>something`s busy with the audio device. Plus, maybe another program has 
>just
>asked for a stereo pair of audio channels (ie, 0 and 2), which means 1 and 
>3
>would be free (if that`s any used to you).

Yes, that is a problem and I'm aware of that, but it was a temporary 
solution. Just a tad note; I belive my routine took into account the amount 
of audio DMA channels who're allocated already, (0-3) and if the result is 
higher than one, the routine returns False, hence I'm not granted any 
access.

> >Using forbid_ and permit _ isn't really a nice thing to do, but it seemed 
>more stable at times.
>
>That is the way to do it..so long as you don`t spend forever in forbid_
>permit_ then you should be alright, though if you do that a lot, say 100
>times a second, you`ll notice the other programs multitasking would go
>jerky. All forbid and permit does is to temporarly disable multitasking,

I just called forbid_/permit_ right before and after i read DMACONR using a 
clean: jsr  -xxx(a6), where xxx corresponds to the neg offset of forbid in 
exec. But I know it only gives me the status of the audio DMA channels at 
that immediate point.

>What you need to do is open the audio device with a priority of -127. This
>means you want exclusive access to the channel combination(s) you 
>specified.

That is exactly what I've been wanting to do, but figuring out what 
arguements Opendevice() takes has been the main problem. I just end up with 
a crash =).If you've got some syntax of it I'd appreciate it very much.

>P.s. If you need any help with the audio device...I`m just about to do
>double buffer sound using the audio device with blitz...so I will have some
>source that might help you ;)

Sounds neat man! Really gr8 if you could show me something about it.
Ey! what about calling Opendevice() in clean machine code? What arguements 
does it take.. hmm..  pri i guess, and a pointer to the name of the device.. 
and a pointer for a structure to return the result to. Hmm.. Just spawning, 
maybe thats easier to do instead of calling it as a normal function, or 
maybe not =). (correct me if i'm wrong, havent got no access to any autodocs 
or anything at work =)

Well, cheerios Dave, thanx for the help!

//Thor


