@NODE "Mail_247" "Re: Audio Control"
 for scott@online.u-net.com; Fri, 30 Apr 1999 21:45:50 +0100
From: "Dave" <dave@nbsamiga.demon.co.uk>
Subject: Re: Audio Control
Date: Fri, 30 Apr 1999 21:43:41 +0100
	boundary="----=_NextPart_000_0010_01BE9352.854EFC20"

------=_NextPart_000_0010_01BE9352.854EFC20
	charset="iso-8859-1"
Encoding: 7bit

Hi Peter and David,


>*CUT* *PASTE*

>Sounds neat man! Really gr8 if you could show me something about it.
>Ey! what about calling Opendevice() in clean machine code? What arguements
>does it take.. hmm..  pri i guess, and a pointer to the name of the
device..
>and a pointer for a structure to return the result to. Hmm.. Just spawning,
>maybe thats easier to do instead of calling it as a normal function, or
>maybe not =). (correct me if i'm wrong, havent got no access to any
autodocs
>or anything at work =)

Well, this is an entirely blitz version (well most of it..the main device
interface is). For my project, I won`t get any more speed by using pure asm,
so it doesn`t matter, and it seems to work in blitz okay for me. If you need
help with a pure asm, then I can give you a hand (it is my first amiga
language...I went basic (cpc464) > pascal > 68k asm > blitz > C > C++). In
asm all you have to do is make the audio request structure by hand (ie,
poking numbers in here and there!). Personally I`d use blitz as it is easier
to handle the structures and offsets, and is more readable...can you not do
both (ie, init the structures using blitz, and then just have asm routines
to do the calls??)......


>*PASTE*

>Could you send that to me too please Dave. I tried converting some C source
>which double buffered the audio device, but I ran into problems as it
relied on
>the SendIO command (or one that sounds like it) which isn't in exec, but in
the
>amiga.lib link library you get with C compilers. Said that was needed
because
>it preserved the flags of the IO request, whereas the normal exec command
>doesn't.


Your sort of right....but the other way around..you should use begin io, as
send io clears the flags, and you don`t want that (though I have no idea
why, probably to do with the fact that the audio device uses flags itself
for it`s own uses!). It doesn`t help with the fact that you only get
supplied with amiga.lib compiled, so we can`t write our own versions of the
commands (like createport). The other answer is to get blitz to read the
.lib files (like .res files) that would be the best option ;) (although more
information would be even better...ie, the source to amiga.lib).


>Anyway, source would be nice. Ta.


 Your wish is my command. Don`t trust this source...I was messing with it,
and it`s not finished...but it worked for me [insert standard disclaimer
here] (played california dreams from hd at 14khz - 3.5mb (ish) file with no
compression). DON`T play compressed 8SVX files with it..it will crash...need
to do some test ones..they seem to have some kind of padding at the front (a
byte maybe?? then the first real byte??)....I`ve not tested it with files
smaller than 1 second of sound. This is going to be part of my video player
(hehehe), so I was just testing the speed of delta compressed iff`s playing
from disk (ie, is it better to have uncompressed sound that takes longer to
read, but no cpu overhead, or compressed iff`s that take half the read time,
but require cpu overhead). Anyway, when I`ve completed this...I`ll send
anyone that asks for the fully working source (though if you make some kind
of player out of it...credit me please!).



Dave

P.s. There`s currently no exit from the play routine, so don`t play a 10
hour long iff sample, unless you want to reset (or have 10 hours to listen
to it!) ;)

P.p.s DON`T use the included portfunctions.bb2 include for anything
else...this is strictly for use with exec devices (well that`s what RKM
libs+devs says).


