@NODE "Mail_248" "Re: Bad Email programs"
 for scott@online.u-net.com; Tue, 27 Apr 1999 17:44:21 +0000
From: "Dave" <dave@nbsamiga.demon.co.uk>
Subject: Re: Bad Email programs
Date: Tue, 27 Apr 1999 17:43:06 +0100
	charset="iso-8859-1"
Encoding: 7bit



>Hi David
>
>On 27-Apr-99, David McMinn wrote:
>>> outlook express could delete them from the pop3 server. I`m not naming
>>> any names (David McMinn...lol), but it`s due to a BAD email send. What
>>> happen
>
>I don't suppose this could be one of those "innocent mistakes" Microsoft
>makes to try to force everybody to use their software?


Hmm..could be ;)....but I tried to recreate the problem, but it works fine
when I try and send a "." on a single to myself, using my yahoo account.
What I did in the end was to telnet to my pop3 server, and see what was
happening. What happened was, when the body for that Re:BFB Sussed ;)) came
down, about 4 lines down, I got <CRLF>"."<CRLF> and then the next line "> I
might do a quick update etc....". Now if you were clever, all the email
program would have to do is to say, well, even though a got a
<CRLF>"."<CRLF>, the body of the message is still comming down, so the
message can`t have stopped, so I continue on with the message. However this
is not what the RFC specifies (no wonder the RFC`s are so strict). So
outlook express couldn`t understand the error message it was getting (">I
might do a quick etc....") after the end of the body. Now I`m not sure how
the single dot got on a line by it`s own...maybe demon stuffed my copy up, I
don`t know...but as someone else also had this problem that`s why I said
something, otherwise I wouldn`t have bothered, but I figured that the
original message must have contained this single dot. Maybe other software
waits till the pop3 server has stop sending data, but how does it detect
error messages when retrieving them??

>Your mails come in fine here, David.  And on everybody else's system too,
>I'm sure, or you would have heard about it long ago...


Yeah, I`ve never had any problems with his mails :)...just that last
one...maybe his software does that to annoy outlook users ;)

Dave


