@NODE "Mail_250" "Re: Bad Email programs"
 for scott@online.u-net.com; Wed, 28 Apr 1999 17:09:27 +0100
From: "Dave" <dave@nbsamiga.demon.co.uk>
Subject: Re: Bad Email programs
Date: Wed, 28 Apr 1999 16:16:10 +0100
	charset="iso-8859-1"
Encoding: 7bit

Hi Paul,

>Dave wrote:
>> Hmm..could be ;)....but I tried to recreate the problem, but it works
>> fine when I try and send a "." on a single to myself, using my yahoo
>> account.
>
>.
>..
>...
>..
>.
>..
>...
>..
>.
>
>Take that!!!! ;^)


YOU FIEND :0.....well all that worked okay here ;)

>> What I did in the end was to telnet to my pop3 server, and see what
>> was happening. What happened was, when the body for that Re:BFB
>> Sussed ;)) came down, about 4 lines down, I got <CRLF>"."<CRLF>
>> and then the next line "> I might do a quick update etc....".
>
>I always thought that old <CRLF>.<CRLF> was for outgoing mail rather
>than for incomming messages. So who's job is it to convert the
>double ".." back to the single "." ? Is that up to the receiving
>mail server, the sending pop3 server or the pop3 client? This
>would mean the problem could be with Pegasus mail, Demons smtp
>server, Demons pop3 server or Outlook Express. Then the final
>observation is the fact that the mail you received didn`t actually
>come from David but rather it came from the mailing-list.


Well, from what I can gather (I may be wrong), but everyone`s job is to add
the extra dot at the front of a line when sending smtp, and then remove it
when receiving (I`d forgotten about this). I think that means that every
exchange of email has to go through this stage (weird or what). So that
message maybe went through 4 smtp servers, so the dot could have been
removed at any stage I guess (well, any of the first 3, as other people had
the problem...so it couldn`t just be demon). I guess I was just a bit
irratated because I was waiting for an email from a client (which didn`t
ever get sent, so in the end it didn`t matter) and that`s why I had a pop at
pegasus ;). (I`m all for free software...but I`m getting a bit fed up with
software that doesn`t conform to reasonable standards....well I would be,
after working on pc`s for what seems like ever!).

Dave



