 for scott@online.u-net.com; Tue, 27 Apr 1999 17:16:56 +0100
From: "Dave" <dave@nbsamiga.demon.co.uk>
Subject: Re: Bad Email programs (Was Re: Pinball algorithms)
Date: Tue, 27 Apr 1999 17:14:33 +0100
	charset="iso-8859-1"
Encoding: 7bit

Hi David,

>> outlook express could delete them from the pop3 server. I`m not naming
any
>> names (David McMinn...lol), but it`s due to a BAD email send. What happen
>
>Sorry, I wasn't aware that was happening. No-one else has said anything
(but
>they maybe haven't noticed it was me).


That`s okay...maybe I`m the only one using demon+pop3+outlook
express....It`s not your fault...but it is a silly mistake in that email
program, as the rfc specifically points this out. (But I should image that
other email programs are more forgiving with the download, ie, not taking
the rfc 100% correctly like outlook express tries to do!).

>> is that the marvelous program david was using thinks it`s okay to do
>> <CRLF>.<CRLF> because there was only a single dot on a line. What the
>
>Whats that? Chr$(13)+Chr$(10)+"."+Chr$(10)+Chr$(13)? But what if you need
that
>in your message?


See below...the guys who designed smtp figured it out....

>> program should have done is to add another . (to make <CRLF>..<CRLF>)
>> which would have been removed automatically by the receiving
>
>OK then, what if you need to do ".." on a line, will the mailer
automatically
>strip it to a single dot?

No...see below too.

>>              The mail data is terminated by a line containing only a
>>             period, that is the character sequence "<CRLF>.<CRLF>" (see
>>             Section 4.5.2 on Transparency).  This is the end of mail data
>>             indication.
>
>Well, thats just bloody ridiculous.


how else do you tell the data to end, when you can use all the 7 bits ascii
codes in your mail?? (ie, you need crlf for a blank line, so everythings
taken). Here`s the answer from RFC 821

   4.5.2.  TRANSPARENCY
         Without some provision for data transparency the character
         sequence "<CRLF>.<CRLF>" ends the mail text and cannot be sent
         by the user.  In general, users are not aware of such
         "forbidden" sequences.  To allow all user composed text to be
         transmitted transparently the following procedures are used.

            1. Before sending a line of mail text the sender-SMTP checks
            the first character of the line.  If it is a period, one
            additional period is inserted at the beginning of the line.

            2. When a line of mail text is received by the receiver-SMTP
            it checks the line.  If the line is composed of a single
            period it is the end of mail.  If the first character is a
            period and there are other characters on the line, the first
            character is deleted.

As you can see, aslong as all email programs follow this, you`ll never get a
problem. Plus any strict smtp mail servers won`t let you post that, as soon
as you send <CRLF>.<CRLF> it will think the mails ended.

>> My advice...check for updates of pegasus with that fixed, or use
something
>> better ;)
>
>I've just checked the website, and there's a new preview version, but no
>mention of that problem, or it being fixed.


I think it only occured when you replied to a previous mail, and when it
added the ">"`s it shoved a single . from the previous line onto a single
line, and forgot to add another . to it, before sending. Or maybe your smtp
server messed it up after it`d been sent (doubtfull though...servers should
simply transport the entire message as is)

>And if you are using OE, I suggest you find something better, strange that
>other mailers can handle this properly, even if it is wrong.


I would, but I`ve checked out other mail programs. I don`t love oe, but it`s
better than almost anything else I`ve seen on the pc, and that the same
reason I use ms office, because there isn`t anything better on the pc. I
just want a simple quick email program, that doesn`t need a lot of setting
or, or messing about with everytime you connect...just click the program,
watch it fetch the mails...read the mails..then quit...that`s all I want
;)...(I`d rather be using yam...but now that I`m doing more websites, I need
to use my pc and it`s faster modem and web page design programs).

I wasn`t out to blame you...you can`t help it...I spent 2 weeks sending out
emails with duplicate html copies at the bottom, before someone told me to
turn it off ;).....stuff happens...it didn`t bother me...just outlook
express couldn`t delete the mail on the server, because it always downloads
everything before deleting...if I was on smtp delivery it wouldn`t have
mattered, but oe doesn`t support that!


Dave



