Hi David,

>> hmm..does freeserve use a secure pop3 server...in which case, you won`t
be
>> able to telnet to it, as the password and login won`t work under telnet.
>
>Ahh thats probably it. I just don't know all this stuff, I can configure
>mailers etc but anything more than that...


hehehe...the funny thing is that in the old days, telnet was your
email/ftp/irc/web/ browser all in one. One of the good things about the
internet (and also one of the bad things) is that all the protocols are
simple text commands. Which you send and receive to and from a server.
Reading the rfc`s to understand the text commands however is more difficult
than actually chatting with a server.

>Guess I'll just have to read my messages for stray periods.


Well, however it got there...I think it`s to do with the line wrap, ie, you
could send a single dot on a line, but if you reply to a mail, and that
pushes a single dot over to a line on its own..then you may get
problems...maybe it`s to do with the = at the end of the line, just before
the crlf, because that tells things that this line wraps round (ie, this
line`s too long to fit on one line, so it`s carried on in the next line). I
wouldn`t worry about it if I were you...there haven`t been any major
complaints (I`m sure you would have heard from the more colourfull residents
of this list if you`d stuff everybody`s mailbox up!)...and I`ll know what to
do next time should i have that problem. I`ve been on this list for over a
year without problem...so take it easy m8 ;)



Dave

P.s. I`ve just thought of something...why did it wrap that line?? Because
instead of putting ".="<CRLF> it could have put ".."<CRLF> weird or what
(ie, no need to wrap as there is only 1 character extra)...as the original
message only has 2 dots. Now I think that must have been down to the mail
program, as surely the smtp wouldn`t mess with the word wrap...would it??




