Hey dave,

> ....but here`s the
> snag...it doesn`t always know how to exactly tell which is the best
> mode...ie, I can get the closest match for say 320x240 (ie, get the lowest
> maximums nominals), but it may have interlace on, or one of the other many
> mistery flags that are set...and I can`t just use the first I find, or the
> last, as there not in any particular order. (ie, I wouldn`t want
> superhires,lace,sprites,dualplayfield for a 320x240 screen)...

Now dont hold me to this, but I think that i once tried to do
something with the asl screenmode requester and it worked. Basically,
in the hook callback program you can get access to the modeID's that
it is trying to add to the requester, using GetDisplayInfoData or
what have you, but you can then pass a `reject' code back from the
hook for every mode. If your filtering of screenmodes rejects all of
the modes offered, i think that the asl requester doesn't appear! This
could possibly be used to get down to business with only the decent
and non-obscure screenmodes, as the asl requester itself only includes
modes which are sort of non-obscure, iykwim. You could store the modes
it asks you to filter, in some kind of array or what have you,
rejecting alll of them so that the asl doesn't appear, and then do
your search based on those modes. It massively reduces the list
because as you've found, if you try and go through the list manually
you get all sorts of strange variations, flags, interlace, numbers of
sprites, ehb, ham and other variants. That might work.

-- 
Paul.

