@NODE "Mail_406" "DLL 2.1"
 for scott@online.u-net.com; Fri, 2 Apr 1999 05:26:06 +0100
From: "Dave" <dave@nbsamiga.demon.co.uk>
Subject: DLL 2.1
Date: Fri, 2 Apr 1999 05:26:53 +0100
	boundary="----=_NextPart_000_0017_01BE7CC9.6D5AF1E0"

------=_NextPart_000_0017_01BE7CC9.6D5AF1E0
	charset="iso-8859-1"
Encoding: 7bit

Hi everyone,

 Here`s my latest (and hopefully last stab) at dynamically linked
lists......I tested all the routines again..so fingers crossed there are no
bugs...(no new ones atleast!)....

 The way you initialise a list has changed, it now returns a pointer to the
head of the list, which you keep and pass to all the routines. See the new
example. I haven`t updated the docs...I`ll do that tomorrow...and I haven`t
corrected the DLLSORT include, which I`ll fix for these lists tomorrow. A
list now takes up a lot less memory, but I still can`t get it to work with
GTListView *sigh*....anyway...the easy way around that is to follow David
McMinn`s example and create a dummy blitz list to give the listview first
(you only ever need one, as you can give it to all your GTListViews to start
with...) and then use GTSetAttrs to change the list to your real list.

 A few examples would be useful to put in the archive, as the current one is
messy and doesn`t really test everything....and it still needs more
extensive testing...and I`d love to turn it into a library..but I have`ny
got the time capt`n.....but as it`s small..it shouldn`t add much compiling
time to your program....(and you can change stuff and make a multi variable
sort routine, by cloning and hacking about with the DLLSORT include...that`s
why it`s seperate for the main routines......)


Happy Linking,

Dave


