@NODE "Mail_441" "Re: Flunking Maths"
 for scott@online.u-net.com; Tue, 6 Apr 1999 18:20:21 +0100
Date: Tue, 06 Apr 1999 15:37:32 +0100
From: Paul Burkey <burkey@bigfoot.com>
X-Accept-Language: en
Subject: Re: Flunking Maths
Encoding: 7bit

Mark Neesam wrote:
> I've been trying to store a display ID as a text string in a preferences
> file for the project I'm working on, and I've hit a problem. Blitz seems
> to be screwing up at maths. Initially I just used a Print command to
> print SDisplay to the file. I was using a Cybergraphics screenmode -
> $40D20002, so it went in to the file as 1087504386. When I read this back
> in and used Val to convert it back to a .long it came up with the answer
> 1087504384. Not right! So I then tried storing the hex version 40D20002,
> loading that in and converting it to decimal, and that got the wrong
> answer too, this time by a larger margin. Any suggestions?
> 
> To test this out I did the blindingly obvious:-
> 
> value$="1087504386"
> value.l=val(value$)
> print value

Why not write the value out as binary number eg:

WriteMem file#,&myvalue,4     ; or ,(SizeOf .type)

Then read it back using:

ReadMem file#,&myvalue,4

Obviously this is no use if your preferences file HAS to be in
pure text but it's not always a requirement. It would also make
the file smaller because instead of writing 10 bytes you`re only
writing 4 :)

I mix and match my file I/O with NPrint and WriteMem commands
all the time. There's never a problem changing from Edit$()
to ReadMem and back again as much as you like. Just use
NPrint for text and WriteMem for numbers. Reading and writing
the file is also faster because there's no unnecessary string
parsing/conversions etc. and the most important thing is
it's 100% safe from the problems you mention here.

Cheers,

Paul


-- 
< Paul Burkey http://www.sneech.freeserve.co.uk >



