@NODE "Mail_513" "Re: Help needed!"
 for scott@online.u-net.com; Fri, 9 Apr 1999 18:46:47 +0100
From: Rick Hodger <rick.thehub@bigfoot.com>
Date: Fri, 09 Apr 1999 16:12:55 +0100
Organization: Pagan Software
Subject: Re: Help needed!

I watched as Pekka Nissinen hammered "Help needed!" out on their
keyboard...


> OK! Lets assume that I have a String gadget (for ex. MUIString 1,"",32),
> that I use to input/Output numeric values. Since there isn't any specific
> Integer Gadget in MUI... (I may be wrong, but I didn't find anything
about
> it in EFMUILIB.quide or in MUI Developer autodocs...) ...I used the
String
> gadget. I tried to make it act like a Integer gadget using line: MUISet
> 1,#MUIA_String_Accept,"0123456789." but it behaved wery strage, so I
> removed the line. But that isn't really THE problem... The REAL trouble
> is, that how can I read the contents of the gadget? Since I can't read
> numeric values using: a=MUIGetString$(1) or print them with: MUISetString
> 1,a
> (I only get that: Can't convert types, blablabla with those lines), I
> managed to read it with this line: a=MUIGet(1,#MUIA_String_Integer) and
> printing with: MUISet 1,#MUIA_String_Integer,a

That's because MUIGetString returns a string ($ type) from that string
gadget, and you're trying to insert that into a byte value.

> But this didn't cure my problem, it only made a new one. This
> reading/printing "method" CAN'T read/print decimals from/to string
gadget!
> For ex. If I have typed number 326.45 to the string gadget, it only
> returns the value 326!! Or from a value 0.1234 I only get 0!! Because of
> the nature of this program, it's important to be able to read and print
> values WITH decimals!

That's because you're asking it to return an integer, integers don't allow
for decimal places.  Try using this function:

Function.f GetMyNos{}
    a$=MUIGetString$(1)
    b.f=Val(a$)
Function Return b.f
End Function

And I think that should return what you're looking for.

> PS. I almost forget, is there a way to use the Slider gadged with
> decimals? It isn't accurate enough to my proggy without them.... (I
> apologize to my poor english..)

I have seen it done in other programs, but I couldn't tell you how...

