@NODE "Mail_538" "Re: Hiding Mr Mouse"
 for scott@online.u-net.com; Sun, 11 Apr 1999 19:23:21 +0000
From: Donovan Reeve <bubby.lnk@ispi.net>
Date: Sun, 11 Apr 1999 12:15:17 +0500
Subject: Re: Hiding Mr Mouse

On 11-Apr-99, Evan Tuer flashed:
>On Sun, 11 Apr 1999 13:11:08 +0000, Chris Deeney wrote:

>> > Well the Amiga mouse pointer is amazing next to Windoze version.
>> 
>> I agree, i think the mouse pointer in an OS can tell u how good it is :)
>> eg. windows mouse pointer - jerky, flickers, not smoth at all
>>     Amiga mouse pointer - lovely and smoth never jerks, Grrrreat! :))

>Perhaps you can tell me what's wrong with my Amiga's mouse pointer
>then? :)  Ever since I installed an 060 card, whenever something
>really processor intensive is going on, like raytracing or certain
>operations in ImageFX, the pointer goes all jerky, although the rest
>of the system seems to still respond reasonably well.  I'm running
>Executive, and it happens slightly worse with it turned off.  
> With the 030, no matter what you threw at it, the pointer was always
>smooth, although you couldn't actually do anything with it :)

>Perhaps it needs oiling.  Or some cheese?  Suggestions please.


  I have seen two thing cause such problems in '040 powered machines and
perhaps '060 powered machines may exibit simular behavior:

- overheating (caused by a slow-turning or failed fan or lint in the
air intakes or something blocking air circulation to the processor).


  The mouse pointer jerking and slowing down was always my first warning
of the overheating problem, after which things gradually slowed down.
If it was hot enough in the room, things got slower in a hurry and might
even stop altogether.

  Fixes

  Clean air passages and entire inside of the computer as necessary.

  Get the ambiant room temperature lower.

  Set a household fan to blow into the INTAKE air ports, but NOT the
exit air ports (exit ports are usually directly from the power supply in
desktop models and tower models, and are on the top of keyboard-in-case
models like the A-1200 and A-500).

  Get a new/better power suply fan.

  Get a CPU fan.




- Low power (caused by an insufficient or failing power pack)

  Fixes

  Get a new power supply

  Get a more powerful power supply

  Apply a new/better fan to the power supply (overheating of the power
supply can lower its output due to thermal breakdown of the rectifiers).



  If you discover your problem is caused by something other than these
two things, let me know, but I have found these to be the main causes of
the erratic pointer behaviour.



cacha later,

Donovan Reeve (bubby.lnk@ispi.net)



