But I'd be interested to see it - I can't get SnoopDos to recognize when the
WB's "Quit" item is hit...

BTW, that menu item DOES work, although it's rather useless.  Try selecting
it after booting from the standard WB floppy (so nothing is run from
WBstartup)

It puts up a requester asking if you're sure, then it will close the WB
"window".
If there are any programs present that were started from WB, it only puts up
an error message.

Unless you have a Shell open, though, you can't do anything except re-boot. 
And you can't have a shell open because the Shell would have been started
from WB, in which case WB can't close...

I suppose you could start a Shell, tell it to start ANOTHER Shell, then
close the first.  But then maybe the 2nd wouldn't let WB close, since it
was started from the first, which started from WB  --  my head hurts!!!!
> 
> Can any of you OS experts tell me if I'm on the right track (ignoring
> Enforcer hits and everything else nasty about this ;)  ?

I don't suppose Enforcer hits would matter, since you are doing a reboot
anyway?

Later...
