@NODE "Mail_564" "Re: In da blitz manual...."
 for scott@online.u-net.com; Sat, 17 Apr 1999 08:24:44 +0100
From: "Tony Rolfe" <edgewater@shoalhaven.net.au>
Organization: Edgewater Motel, Burrill Lake, NSW 2539 Australia
Date: 17 Apr 99 16:43:04 +1000
Subject: Re: In da blitz manual....
Encoding: 7bit

On Fri, 16 Apr 1999 12:14:33 +0100 stocksjames said:
> Rob Hutchinson wrote:
> > Oh yeah, BTW - Does `Make Smallest code' actually do anything what so ever?

It seems to work as follows:

If you have it set off (as I do) and you set the various amounts in
the Compiler options then, provided these valus are all sufficient,
they remain unchanged and you have a single-pass compile.  If any one
value is insufficient then you get the dreaded message and if you
click "make smallest" they ALL get set to the smallest usable value.  

If you have it set on you get a two pass compile, which takes longer,
but you never get the message.

It's a trade-off between compile time and memory usage.

Since my program takes six minutres (count them) for a single-pass
compile, I set the values BIG for test compiless and always save
before making an executable.

Anyway, that's the way (I think) it works.

Cheers.

-- 
Tony Rolfe
Amiga 2000, 68030/25, 1+4Mb
www.shoalhaven.net.au/edgewater

