@NODE "Mail_617" "Re: Lots of OS questions to feed on ;)"
 for scott@online.u-net.com; Thu, 22 Apr 1999 10:32:08 +0100
From: "David McMinn" <D.Mcminn@eee.rgu.ac.uk>
Organization: The Robert Gordon University, E&EE
Date: Thu, 22 Apr 1999 10:29:40 +0100
encoding: Quoted-printable
Subject: Re: Lots of OS questions to feed on ;)

> 2, SuperBitmaps,.. As in the likes of the MUI texted mcc, IE which can b=
e
>     scrolled with a GTScroller or similar.. I dont know anything about
>     superbitmaps. Can anyone enlighten me?

I doubt whether a texted mcc would use a superbitmap. That would involve h=
aving 
a huuuuuuuge bitmap, which could be any lenghth, as you can enter as many 
newlines as possible. It probably uses the srcoller positions to determine=
 how 
many lines have been skipped after using the scroller, or what the top lin=
e 
should be.

And if you do want to know about superbitmaps, don't look at me.

> 4, How do I free a .image ? First thing I tried FreeImage_ but obviously
>     doesn`t exist ;) ?? As my program is leaking chip and fast :( grante=
d
>     only a bit, but a bit is a bit, and it turns into a lot ;))))

It depends how you've allocated it. If you allocated it with AllocRaster_ =
or 
maybe AllocBitMap_ or AllocMem_ then you should use the appropriate Free 
routine. If you're trying to free memory that you didn't allocate (i.e. if=
 you 
are trying to free an image from an icon :) then you're asking for trouble=
.

> 5, Anyone know how the BitmapScale_ and ClipBlit_ commands work?
>     ClipBlit_ seems as though it could do the trick for my proggie.
>     I take it it just grabs a section of one RastPort and and clips it
>     into another? IE like using Bitmap... Getashape... Blit ???

; You need bitmaps for this. If you ain't using Blitz bitmaps, then either=
 use 
; OS ones or cludge something (an image? ;)into one.
DEFTYPE.w
w1=3D20
h1=3D20
BitMap 0,w1,h1,3  ; Our source bitmap

; Work out dimensions of destination bitmap, the whole things gonna be sca=
led
; up 2:1 You could probably also calculate this by "hand".
w2=3DScalerDiv_(w1,2,1)
h2=3DScalerDiv_(h1,2,1)

BitMap 1,w2,h2,3  ; Our dest bitmap

DEFTYPE.BitScaleArgs bsa
bsa\bsa_SrcX=3D0 ; Start co-ordinate of area to scale
bsa\bsa_SrcY=3D0
bsa\bsa_SrcWidth=3Dw1 ; dimensions of area to scale
bsa\bsa_SrcHeight=3Dh1
bsa\bsa_SrcXFactor=3D1 ; part of the ratio for scaling in x direction
bsa\bsa_SrcYFactor=3D1 ; ditto, for y
bsa\bsa_DestX=3D0 ; Start co-ordinate to put scaled data
bsa\bsa_DestY=3D0
bsa\bsa_DestWidth=3Dw2 ; Size of scaled area (set by function, I don't kno=
w if
bsa\bsa_DestHeight=3Dh2 ; you need to set them
bsa\bsa_DestXFactor=3D2 ; part of the ratio for scaling in x direction
bsa\bsa_DestYFactor=3D2 ; ditto for y
bsa\bsa_SrcBitMap=3DAddr BitMap(0)
bsa\bsa_DestBitMap=3DAddr BitMap(1)
bsa\bsa_Flags=3D0 ; must be done

BitMapScale_(&bsa)

ClipBlit_ should be easy to use, just feed it pointers to source and dest 
rastports, x and y co-ordinates for source and dest and width and height. 
MinTerm is described in the hardware RKRM, but three common ones are:

$C0 - straight copy
$30 - inverts the source
$50 - ignores source and inverts destination


