@NODE "Mail_618" "Re: Lots of OS questions to feed on ;)"
 for scott@online.u-net.com; Thu, 22 Apr 1999 11:29:09 +0100
From: Curt Esser <camge@ix.netcom.com>
Date: Wed, 21 Apr 1999 16:36:56 -0500
Subject: Re: Lots of OS questions to feed on ;)

--BOUNDARY.1748417256.5

Hi Rob

On 21-Apr-99, Rob Hutchinson wrote:
> Hello,
> 
>    Can someone *please* help me with the following,.. 
> 
> 1, Is there any way to do nice buffered blits to a window? lots of
> programs
>    do it so it must be possible?

It's not really possible, as a Window has only one bitmap.  However,
depending on the situation, there are various tricks I've tried that seem
to work OK.

What exactly are you trying to do  (ie, is this window on WB, or your own
custom screen, is it a game, how big are the "Blits", etc...)
> 
> 2, SuperBitmaps,.. As in the likes of the MUI texted mcc, IE which can be
>    scrolled with a GTScroller or similar.. I dont know anything about 
>    superbitmaps. Can anyone enlighten me?

I don't know about how MUI works, but a standard SuperBitmap is simply a
Bitmap that is too big to fit all at once on the Screen or Window.  So the
visible part of the display is like looking through the viewfinder of a
camera - you only see a part of the "scene" in the rectangular area of the
viewfinder, although it's all out there - to see other parts, you scroll
around by some method.

> 
> 4, How do I free a .image ? First thing I tried FreeImage_ but obviously
>    doesn`t exist ;) ?? As my program is leaking chip and fast :( granted
>    only a bit, but a bit is a bit, and it turns into a lot ;))))

Assuming you have allocated the memory and loaded the .image yourself
through the OS commands, you need to FreeMem_ it yourself when you don't
need it any more.

> and lastly, <Phew>
> 
> 6, What is the best way to detect double-clicks in windows?

I've attached an email on the subject.

> And also I`ve decided to create my own catalog format
> for my program ;).. then I have complete control over it. I can also have
> a language menu item that leads to a mutually-exclusive set of options for
> the languages ;). So users can change languages "on-the-fly" (is it just
> me or does that saying crop up a lot in here?) ;)

Yes, this is what I did too.  The "Locale Catalogs" are just plain text
files.
I also included commented lines (which my program ignores when loading) so
you can include instructions for translators, etc.  Like "make sure this
line is no longer than 12 characters" or whetever...

Later...
-- 
Desk: A wastebin with drawers.

                                    Yours electronically,
                                    Curt Esser
                                    camge@ix.netcom.com
                                    http://members.xoom.com/Curt_Esser/


--BOUNDARY.1748417256.5
Content-Disposition: attachment; filename="DoubleClick"
Encoding: quoted-printable
Content-Description: Luca Carminati <toffi@spm.it>

On 20-Set-98, Eoghann Irving wrote:

>>> Is there any way of reading the double click speed from WB prefs?
>>> At the moment my program just uses a fixed value when watching for do=
uble
>>> clicks.

>> what about the Intuition function DoubleClick_?

>That looks very promising if I can just figure out exactly how to use it=
=2E

>I think it compares the first two values you give it (seconds and
>microseconds with the second two values alos seconds and microseconds)

>All I have to do now is work out how to measure the time in seconds
>and microseconds. :)

Ok, here is the code you need:

--------------------

WBStartup

NoCli

DEFTYPE .l SSec,SMic,CSec,CMic

FindScreen 0

GTButton 0,51,4,4,100,20,"Click here",0

Window 0,50,50,200,50,$100e,"Test",1,2

AttachGTList 0,0

Repeat
  ev.l=3DWaitEvent
  If ev=3D$40
    CurrentTime_ &CSec,&CMic
    If DoubleClick_(SSec,SMic,CSec,CMic)
      EZRequest "Double clicked!!!"
    EndIf
    SSec=3DCSec:SMic=3DCMic
  EndIf
Until ev=3D$200

End

------------------

See ya...




-- =

Best regards,

Luca.

