@NODE "Mail_636" "Re: MIDI Question :)"
 for scott@online.u-net.com; Wed, 21 Apr 1999 00:43:42 +0000
From: amorel <amorel@xs4all.nl>
Date: Wed, 21 Apr 1999 01:24:11 +0500
Subject: Re: MIDI Question :)

On 21-Apr-99, Rui Carvalho wrote:
C=Hello,

C=I'm going to buy a midi interface to start gearing some equipment...
C=Here's my doubt...

Hisoft has a nice midi interface.

C=How many devices can you hook up into a midi port?
C=Is it like SCSI, one device hooked up on to the other or is it 1 port 1
C=device?

Normally a midi interface has 1 midi in, 2 out and 1 through. U connect a
midi out to a midi in of a midi device, then to connect more u either
connect another midi device to midi out of the interface or connect it to
midi through on the first midi device(if it has this). When u use Amiga as
a midi device controlled by another controller/sequencer u it works the
same, but then from that device`s point of view.

The limit of connecting device with the through method is 16, as that is
the amount of midi channels you can get. I guess u can get even more, but
than u need to either have some fancier interface or connect more
devices on 1 midi channel. But with 16 devices connected on 1 midi out and
then further on midi throughs gives some timing problems, signal takes
long to reach last devices. So then u`d better do 8 at midi out 1 and 8 at
midi out 2. If you got only 2 devices its best to connect one at midi out
1 and the other at midi out 2.

Midi through just lets the midi signal travle further without any changhe.

Hope this helps.

-- 
