>On the second point, MIDI interfaces come equipped with Three ports, a MIDI
>In, A MIDI Out, and a MIDI Thru. I don't think it is like SCSI. I was gonna
>do an ASCII diagram, but I forgot how to layout the interfaces/devices

>Basically, you have a MIDI In port on the interface and your MIDI keyboard
>or whatever. You also have a MIDI Out on both of these.

>Then, on some interfaces (not on the cu amiga one) you will have a MIDI
>Thru, and there should also be a MIDI thru on the device. This may only be
>on General MIDI devices. You connect the In port on the interface to the
>MIDI Out on the device, and the Out on the interface to the In on the
>device.

>You also can use the Thru port. Using this, I think you connect the
>interface to a device, by an Out(interface)-->In(1st device), and then on
>the device, you do a Thru(1st device)-->In(other device) and then on the
>2nd device, you do a Out(2nd device)-->In(interface)

>Someone please tell me if this is wrong, in case i connect them up wrong and
>blow up my keyboards (but don't let that put you off Rui, I don't think it
>would do any damage!)


  You cannot damage MIDI equiptment by hooking the MIDI cables up to the
wrong MIDI port as they are all isolated.  Just dont plug it into a standard
serial port or a monitor port or a C-64 disk-drive port.  ;)


   For complete information on MIDI go to www.midi.org


cacha later,

Donovan Reeve (bubby.lnk@ispi.net)



