@NODE "Mail_641" "Re: Mildred problems"
 for scott@online.u-net.com; Fri, 9 Apr 1999 19:56:33 +0100
From: "Paul" <paulwest@stationone.demon.co.uk>
Organization: private
Date: 9 Apr 99 19:54:40 +0000
Subject: Re: Mildred problems
Encoding: 7bit

Hi Oliver,

> I have been writting a simple game using mildred which i was getting
> along with nicly until i installed a bvision graphics card into my
> computer and tryed to open it on a cybergraphics screen the screen
> opens but the bitmap is not attached any ideas i have attached the
> main graphics code below.
> 
> could some one at least show me how to display a bitmap in a screen as
> i might be able to do the rest then the mscreen2 example is not
> helping at all i find it is beyond my grasp and it does not compile it
> complains about *ScrVP._ViewPort=0 it says it is not defined.

This is simply that the newtype ._ViewPort isn't found in the
amigalibs.res include. If this is the case, try .ViewPort without the
underscore, or try lowercase. You may find that the same applies to a
_Screen newtype, which you might have to change to .Screen

> 
> this is the main graphics loop as i was using with agabut does not
> work under cybergraphx.

Ok the main problem is that you cannot specify a normal blitz bitmap
to use as the cybergraphics display. You have to use screentags and
specify that there is no bitmap to use, so that it will generate its
own one. You have to let it do this because cybergraphics or picasso96
will have patched the various routines in the o/s to cause screens to
open with `extended' bitmap structures in order to properly support
the rtg.

So, let the screentags open its own bitmap and grab that bitmap using
something like ScreensBitmap. However, it doesn't end there. You
cannot use and do not need to use Mc2p to output to the graphics card.
Mc2p does a chunky-to-planar conversion, which is so that you can view
the chunky data on the AGA planar display. With graphics cards, they
store their data in chunky format so what you have to do is `copy' the
bitmap contents to the graphics card, rather than convert it into
planar. To do this, you need to use something such as
WritePixelArray8. If you want to use linemodulos though (a display
smaller than the total width of the bitmap), you will need to use
either the o/s 3.1 WriteChunkyPixels_(), or the WritePixelArray_()
from the cybergraphics library. It is also possible to cludge a
mildred bitmap onto the graphics card mem and use MScroll or
MBlockScroll to output.

All these methods are done in MScreen2.lha, although perhaps more
comprehensively than is necessary for a simple rtg. In order to access
the WritePixelArray_() function you will need to install the blitz lib
for cybergraphics library, although it is possible that
WritePixelArray8_ from the normal graphics lib will suffice.

Mc2p is only for AGA output, and graphics cards need to use a
different routine to get the data to the display. Those are your two
reasons why it isn't working on the blizzardvision thingy.

-- 
Paul.

IRC: #amiga, Dalnet: #blitz
WWW: http://www.stationone.demon.co.uk
E-M: paul@stationone.demon.co.uk


