@NODE "Mail_667" "Re: More Mildred Questions"
 for scott@online.u-net.com; Fri, 9 Apr 1999 19:07:19 +0100
From: "Paul" <paulwest@stationone.demon.co.uk>
Organization: private
Date: 9 Apr 99 19:06:12 +0000
Subject: Re: More Mildred Questions
Encoding: 7bit

Jake,

> Mc2pWindow 0,320,200
> MBitmap 0,320,200
> MPlanar16ToBitmap 0,Bank(0)
> LoadShapes 0,"blitz2:gfx/nin.shapes"
> MShape 0,42,100
> MPlanar16ToShape 0,Bank(0),42,100,320,200
> MMakeCookie 0
> MQueue 0,1 ; 1 shape

You can't use the blitz command LoadShapes to load in mildred shapes,
they're not in chunky format. What you should do is load in the shapes
as you are (with LoadShapes), then for each shape in the bank, blit it
to the blitz bitmap using `Blit', then you can do MShape to initialise
a new mildred shape and MPlanar16ToShape to copy the planar shape data
from the planar bitmap into the chunky shape. Ie basically you've
gotta convert the planar shapes into chunky shapes. Just doing MShape
and MPlanar16ToShape won't achieve that cus there'd be no shape on the
bitmap, pointed to by Bank(0). Also, because the shape is very
unlikely to be 320x200, and your MShape is 42x100 (which btw is not
legal as the width should be a multiple of 4), you will need to use
the longer version of the MPlanar16ToShape command, such as
MPlanar16ToShape 0,Bank(0),48,100,320,200, something like that. Note
that the MPlanar16ToShape command requires the width of the area being
converted to be a multiple of 16!!

-- 
Paul.

