@NODE "Mail_693" "Music Programs"
 for scott@online.u-net.com; Sat, 24 Apr 1999 21:09:50 +0100
From: Donovan Reeve <bubby.lnk@ispi.net>
Date: Sat, 24 Apr 1999 14:03:25 +0500
Subject: Music Programs

On 24-Apr-99, amorel flashed:

>Yeah so? It`s fun, better than half done games ;-) And as I love music and
>listening to it on my Amiga and I wont try beating SoundStudio I figured a
>player might be a good choice. Also I wasnt satisfied with the over
>featured players which exist. 


  I wish someone WOULD try beating SoundStudio as I'm not to happy with it.
It is not very intuitive and the MIDI support is very cheezy.  The interface
is dodgy also IMHO but I could live with that if the software would do what
I need it to.
  The Amiga needs a good, easy to use but full featured MIDI sequencer, one
which supports ALL of the MIDI standard and command set instead of just a
uselessly small part of it.
  Yeah, I have Bars and Pipes, and it just doesn't click with me.
  Actually I would be perfectly happy with Deluxe Music if it fully and
properly supported MIDI and had a few other inadequacys addressed such as the
attrocious idea that there should only be 8 levels of volume when the Amiga
itself supports so many more levels, and the inadequite handling of expression
and ASDR envelopes.  I was always hoping that Electronic Arts would take yet
one more whack at it and get it right.

  Oh, well...  I suppose it will never happen unless I do it myself, which I
am getting more and more tempted to try.  Maybe some of you who have had some
experience with such things would be willing to give me a few pointers if I
did?


>C=I know no one really cares, but I'll just say I won't grab -any- of them,
>C=until
>C=they support MOD/XM/OSS/MED/OctaMED/S3M/Multitracker, in order of
importance

>Would you be willing to pay for such a player? Quite some people seem to
>use my program, but forget it`s shareware($5). I`m an umemployed
>programmer(information analyst officially :). In other words, I have not
>yet had a single registration request, but oh well I never expected that
>in the first place.

  Yeah, I know what you mean.  I had two shareware programs released back
in the early 90s, and even then almost no-one paid me even though many
wrote and told me how great they were and suggested additions to them.
One of my programs even got pretty good reviews in five different Amiga
magazines and was advertised for years in PD/Shareware collections, but
I got almost nothing accept letters wanting to know when the next version
was coming out.  There was one group of people who were the ones who
usually paid me and that was those in the U.S. military.  I got letters
(and checks) from all over the world from them.  Ever since then I have
had an especially soft spot for them.


cacha later,

Donovan Reeve (bubby.lnk@ispi.net)



