@NODE "Mail_705" "Re: Off Topic but really urgent! :)"
 for scott@online.u-net.com; Wed, 14 Apr 1999 18:13:49 +0100
From: "Paul" <paulwest@stationone.demon.co.uk>
Organization: private
Date: 14 Apr 99 18:02:28 +0000
Subject: Re: Off Topic but really urgent! :)
Encoding: 7bit

> Hello all.
> 
> I'm here at college at the moment and I'm doing this extreemly boring and
> very hard Procedural Program Design assignment. I'm currently stuck on a
> question which asks `What is a dry test run?'. I kinda know what it is but i
> can't really expand on it. Any ideas or suggestions?

A dry run is where you emulate what the program will do, but on paper.
You list your variables in columns and list the steps down the
lefthand side. Then for each step of the program you put in what
effect it has so that you keep track of the variable contents. Just
sort of helps you to see where any problems might be occuring and to
monitor what's going on in the program. There's not much more you can
say about it really. You just use it for showing what the program does
at each stop so that you can explain what's happening sorta thing.

-- 
Paul.

