@NODE "Mail_707" "Re: Off Topic but really urgent! :)"
 for scott@online.u-net.com; Wed, 14 Apr 1999 15:06:07 +0000
From: "Dave" <dave@nbsamiga.demon.co.uk>
Subject: Re: Off Topic but really urgent! :)
Date: Wed, 14 Apr 1999 15:00:25 +0100
	charset="iso-8859-1"
Encoding: 7bit

>Hello all.
>
>I'm here at college at the moment and I'm doing this extreemly boring and
>very hard Procedural Program Design assignment. I'm currently stuck on a
>question which asks `What is a dry test run?'. I kinda know what it is but
i
>can't really expand on it. Any ideas or suggestions?


Pretty off topic ;)....dry test run...lemme think back to my pascal lessons
at college...

A dry test run simply means that once you have writen you program on paper,
you prentend that you are the interpreter (or simply a computer running your
program), and step through the instructions and keep track of what your
progam does, by supplying predetermined input and following the program
flow, and checking that the output matches your expected output. ie..

input a
b=0
for loop=0 to 2
 b=b+a
next loop
print b

Your dry run would look something like this with an input of 20, and an
expected output of 40

Input A                      (enter 20) A=20
b=0                           A=20, B=0
for loop=0 to 1         A=20, B=0, loop=0
b=b+a                       A=20, B=20, loop=0
next loop                   A=20, B=20, loop=1
b=b+a                       A=20, B=40, loop=1
next loop                   A=20,B=40, loop=2
print b                        (output 40)


>BTW. Anyone solved my MUIListView problem yet? :) I'm really stuuuuck!


Not me...I one of those many millions of ppl that hate mui ;)


>Thanks a million and one
>Matt.


I should think so...and if you get 0 out of a 100%...don`t blame me ;)

Dave




