@NODE "Mail_736" "Overflow Errors"
 for scott@online.u-net.com; Mon, 26 Apr 1999 21:57:32 +0000
From: Curt Esser <camge@ix.netcom.com>
Date: Mon, 26 Apr 1999 15:48:32 -0500
Subject: Overflow Errors

Hi Tony

On 26-Apr-99, Tony Rolfe wrote:
> Curt Esser wrote:
>> 
>> [snip VP stuff]
>> 
>>> Before freeing a GTlist, or ending your program, you put in a dummy
>>> errortrap:
>>> 
>>> SetErr
>>> EndSetErr
>>> 
>>> Free GTList 0
>>> 
>>> ClrErr
>>> 
> Could you do the same sort of thing for something you know is going to
> give an "Overflow Error"?   I absolutely must have negative values in
> my pgm so I get Overflow errors when I try to do something like:
>    Fred.w & %ffff - #some_flag.

I'm guessing you meant Fred.w & $ffff?  % means a binary number, which can
only be 1's and 0's, like %00010111.

Fred & $ffff would give you the UNSIGNED value of Fred - but you said you
wanted to use the negative values?  Maybe this is the problem...  Try just
Fred.w - #some_flag

Anyway, Overflow Error means one of two things:

1) You have accidentaly exceeded the capacity of the variable.  A signed
word can hold from -32768 to +32768 so if for example you try to put -35000
or +59123 into Fred you will get an Overflow Error.  In this case you
should use a long for Fred rather than a word  (or you will get incorrect
results from your program)

2) You have PURPOSELY exceeded the SIGNED capacity of the variable. For
example, let's say you want to call a System routine that requires an
UNSIGNED word.  In this case, you would turn Overflow Errors off in the
debugger options and put whatever positive value you need into Fred. (up to
the capacity of an UNSIGNED word, which is any positive value from 0 to
65536) The system will still read it correctly, and you can read the
correct unsigned value from it with:

Nprint Fred & $ffff

In either case, an error trap won't help - this is a debugger (programmer)
error, not a system error.  In other words, it won't cause a crash - only
incorrect results in you program.

Maybe this example will help to explain it a bit:

Fred.w=-1368
Nprint Fred            ;the signed value of Fred
Nprint Fred & $ffff    ;the unsigned value
Mousewait
End

I hope this helps...

                                    Yours electronically,
                                    Curt Esser
                                    camge@ix.netcom.com
                                    http://members.xoom.com/Curt_Esser/



