I Actually meant Fred.w & ($ffff - #SomeFlag), trying to set the flag
value off without changing the other flags.

> 
> Fred & $ffff would give you the UNSIGNED value of Fred - but you
> said you wanted to use the negative values?  Maybe this is the problem... 
> Try just   Fred.w - #some_flag

I meant that I need negative values for other variables in my program
so I can't just set Overflow Errors off.     I was actually trying to
unset the TabCycle flag in a gadget.   The command was (something
like)   *Gadget\Flags & ($ffff-#GFLG_TABCYCLE)   which gave me an
overflow error.   I fixed it by using $7fff since the high-order bit
is usually zero anyway.   That is, however, a bit inelegant, since
not all flags have a zero high order bit.  I was wondering if using
the set err, end err, clear err technique would stop the overflow
error when using $ffff
> 
> Anyway, Overflow Error means one of two things:
<Snip>

Thanks, I did understand (almost).  The problem is with having to
exceed the signed capacity in one variable, but needing negative
values in others (Why oh why doesn't Blitz have a signed/unsigned
option on the DEFTYPE command??).

Thanks for the help.


