@NODE "Mail_747" "Re: Pinball Algorithms 2"
 for scott@online.u-net.com; Thu, 29 Apr 1999 02:09:05 +0000
From: Anton Reinauer <anton@ww.co.nz>
Date: Thu, 29 Apr 1999 12:14:57 +1200
Subject: Re: Pinball Algorithms 2

On 29-Apr-99, Linda Bell wrote:
> I`ve been to the library today to look at the maths/physics books -
> unfortunately, I was one of those people at school who didn`t pay much
> attention - assuming that, on the off-chance I might need to know
> something, I could look it up in a book - unfortunately, I don`t know
> what jargon-type-words I should be looking for - i.e. what`s
> trigonometry - I only payed attention to binary numbers in maths.
> 
> What keywords am I looking for?

  Velocity (speed), mass, acceleration, momentum, angle of deflection
(Physics-Mechanics), and yes trigonometry is at the base of it all- I'd
suggest getting into that if you want to do this game :-) 
  The easier part is working out how a ball will bounce off a flat
surface (at any angle). You have to calculate the x and y components of
it's velocity separately. For a curved surface you're looking at
calculating the tangent at the point of the curve where the ball hits,
and then using that as your flat surface to bounce off.
  If two balls are the same mass/weight then you can ignore the momentum
stuff, and just calculate the x and y velocity components. Again you
use tangents (calculate the tangent on each ball- it should be the same
for both if the balls are the same size), as they're not likely to
strike each other head on. 

> I was considering learning C - since Dice3.1 is now on Aminet, so I
> might trawl the web for something. I registered the original Dice, but
> I had no Amiga-specific info on loading IFFs, etc. - that`s why I
> turned to Blitz.
  
 If you can read the C you could always convert it to Blitz.

 Seeya- Anton

-- 
        Anton Reinauer <anton@ww.co.nz>
       


