@NODE "Mail_757" "Re: PS animation player"
 for scott@online.u-net.com; Wed, 7 Apr 1999 17:11:12 +0100
From: "Dave" <dave@nbsamiga.demon.co.uk>
Subject: Re: PS animation player
Date: Wed, 7 Apr 1999 17:04:15 +0100
	charset="iso-8859-1"
Encoding: 7bit

   The MDEC is the propriety video decompression hardware. It gives
fullscreen
   high-quality video playback and also decompress graphics into VRAM.
   *    Motion JPEG Hardware Decompression Engine
   *   Operating performance 80 MIPS (Clearing Capacity)
   *    Directly connected to CPU bus
   *    Compatible with MPEG1, H.261 files (both via additional hardware?)


Doesn`t propriety mean we can`t use it for our own movies?? (ie, like
compuserves gif, and ibm`s compression routines)...or does that just mean
the hardware??


This is off some mac quicktime plugin to play MDEC`s on the mac....


Benchmarks:

System: Power Center 132 / 96 mb ram / 512 kb l2 cache / Quantum Atlas II F
& W Ultra SCSI 3 hard drive / Standard video with 2 mb v-ram / Mac OS 8.1 /
QT 3.0 / QT MDEC 1.0a2 / Mac OS Easy Open / X-Mount 1.0a1

System Tested with: FF7_INTRO.MDEC mdec encoded movie running QT MDEC 1.0a2
and Movie Player 3.0 PRO. Movie Player's ram allocation was increased to
24.5 MB.

The FF7_INTRO.MDEC (45 seconds, 38.5 MB) movie was tested at both 230x320
and 640x480 resolutions. MDEC movies are encoded at 640x480 and 230x320 and
operate at a maximum of 300 kilobytes a second (a Playstation disc is always
optimized for 2x speed).

230x320 did pretty ok and scored an average of 13.5 fps. However 640x480 did
pretty ok and scored an average of 8.5 fps. 640x480 was played in Movie
Player's "full screen" mode.


230x320@13.5fps ?? 45 seconds for 38.5mb??. Does that means both a 640x480
and a 230x320 version in one file...but that would be nuts...surely?? It
doesn`t sound like the best format to me...but then I don`t own a
playstation....but, you have to realise that the intros aren`t always great
on pc games either....my friend just purchased shogo...and the intro is
like, very low res, and skips vertical lines (for speed I`d guess)...looked
horrible though!

Dave



