@NODE "Mail_761" "Re: QAngle problem (was: Basic Trig)"
 for scott@online.u-net.com; Tue, 20 Apr 1999 09:25:17 +0100
From: "Simon Hitchen" <simon@gadge.u-net.com>
Organization: Gadge Software
Date: 20 Apr 99 09:20:33 +0100
Subject: Re: QAngle problem (was: Basic Trig)
Encoding: 7bit

Hello Liz,
 
> There is a command in Blitz called QAngle which returns the angle between 2
> 2D points. However it appears to return the wrong values. It says it returns
> between 0 and 1 with 1=360deg. However with 2 points in a vertical line I
> should get 0.5 returned which would equate to 180deg but I am getting around
> 0.2 being returned. Therefore can someone remind me of the trig formulas for
> working out the angle 'by hand'. 

This may be a little late now but....

QAngle (which I've just been investigating) does return the correct
values between 0 and 1, BUT, it doesn't count "north" as 0 IYSWIM.

It seems to use "east" as the start point.

So: A-----B  QAngle(10,10,100,10) returns 0


    A
    |
    |
    |
    B        QAngle(10,10,10,100) returns .25


    B-----A  QAngle(100,10,10,10) returns .5


    B
    |
    |
    |
    A        QAngle(10,100,10,10) returns .75


So you'd have to do something like:

  correctedvalue.q = QWrap(QAngle(x,y,x2,y2)+0.25,0,1)

to get "north" as 0 (on a scale of 0 -> 1)


-- 

Bye f'now

Simon

