@NODE "Mail_766" "Re: QAngle problem (was: Basic Trig)"
 for scott@online.u-net.com; Wed, 21 Apr 1999 02:18:26 +0100
From: "Dave" <dave@nbsamiga.demon.co.uk>
Subject: Re: QAngle problem (was: Basic Trig)
Date: Wed, 21 Apr 1999 02:15:58 +0100
	charset="iso-8859-1"
Encoding: 7bit

Hi,

>Hmmm... I always assumed a clockwise rotation for angles with:
>
>0    being north
>90   being east
>180  being south
>270  being west


Try this code....

WBStartup
DEFTYPE.w

Screen 0,2,"Sine Test From My GCSE Maths Lessons"

ScreensBitMap 0,0

x.w=140:y.w=100:x1.w=50:y1.w=100

degtorad.q=Pi/180.0

For loop=0 To 356 Step 2
  dist.f=Sin(loop*degtorad)*40:dist2.f=Cos(loop*degtorad)*40
  Line x,y,x,y+dist,1:Line x1,y1,x1+dist2,y1+dist,2
  x+1:VWait
Next loop


MouseWait

End

This was something I had to do for maths at school (ie, draw a sine wave by
using the points of a circle...)....funny thing is though, that in my school
a sine wave goes up, then down...and not down then up as in
this....hmmmmm....doh...of course, when I drew the sine wave at school, the
middle line was zero, and minus was below the line, and plus was above it (I
think so...anyway...that`d explain it!...ie, the reason this is drawn
inversed)

so

0 - east
90 - south
180 - west
270 - north

by my reckoning anyway,

Dave


