@NODE "Mail_776" "Re: Randomize EEEEK!"
 for scott@online.u-net.com; Wed, 28 Apr 1999 19:35:42 +0000
From: "Dave" <dave@nbsamiga.demon.co.uk>
Subject: Re: Randomize EEEEK!
Date: Wed, 28 Apr 1999 19:31:56 +0100
	charset="iso-8859-1"
Encoding: 7bit

Hi,

>[=>
>[=> I always use something like the following
>[=>
>[=> nprint int(rnd(1.0)*200000.0))
>
>Stoppid question? But what does this:
>
>Lofs.l=2000000.0
>For a=0 To 100
>  NPrint Int(Rnd(1.0)*Lofs)
>Next

>Return a load of Minus numbers?

I have no idea...it should always return 0, as when you times say, 0.5 by a
long, it uses long mulutiples, so it would first change 0.5 to a long, and
give 0 * lofs. (ie, try nprint rnd(1.0)*200000 and it should always be 0, as
the 200000 without the .0 will be converted into a long..I think)

>I guess its the types?
>I had to change it to:

>Lofs.s="2000000.0"
>For a=0 To 100
>  NPrint Int(Rnd(1.0)*Val(Lofs))
>Next


that`s different ;)...if you need it to be a number, use .f for float.

>Which works fine ;).. But it`s a bit of a bodge ;)
>Oh well, whatever works ;)

I guess it doesn`t matter as long as it works...by the way, it may not be
able to return you maximum value, as I think rnd(1.0) will only return
0.0000 to 0.9999 (I think..not checked it though)

Dave


