@NODE "Mail_785" "Re: Recursive directories and dynamic data storage"
 for scott@online.u-net.com; Sat, 3 Apr 1999 20:20:13 +0100
From: Blitzwing <blitzwing@goldweb.com.au>
Date: Sun, 04 Apr 1999 05:19:29 +1000
Subject: Re: Recursive directories and dynamic data storage

> 1) scan the first DIR
> 2) add the paths of all sub directories to the list (string array or 
> whatever)
> 3) go through the list from top to bottom, scanning each directory on 
> the list and adding the path of any DIRs to the end of the list.
> 4) continue going through the list until complete (i.e. you've got to 
> the bottom of the list)

I'd try something like this,

1> scan root dir, note number of sub dirs, set a counter to keep track of
which sub dir you're going into
2> scan into sub dir, note number of sub-sub dirs, set a counter to keep
track of the next level of sub dir you're going into.
3> repeat until you get a dir empty or just files
4> go back up 1 level
5> scan next subdir same method

think of it the way CLI does a dir scan, ie "Dir ALL"

I'll show it in more detail if you're interested, but my method doesn't
generate a list of dirs like yours does, but it does use less memory,
depends what you realy need to scan subdirs for...

Blitzwing
