@NODE "Mail_802" "Re: Shading techniques (was SV: Grand Theft AMiGA)"
 for scott@online.u-net.com; Fri, 2 Apr 1999 15:44:17 +0100
Date: Fri, 02 Apr 1999 15:37:37 +0100
From: Paul Burkey <burkey@bigfoot.com>
X-Accept-Language: en
Subject: Re: Shading techniques (was SV: Grand Theft AMiGA)
Encoding: quoted-printable

"Andreas H=E5kansson" wrote:
> >Yeah, don`t nock the old Look Up Tables too much. They're usefull for
> >storing information that can take a LOT of calculating. I use LUT's a
> >great deal this week to add Gouraud shaded texturemapping with dithere=
d
> >texture blending to Foundation.
>
> fell like sharing how you did this? I'd really like to use this in
> our game, this enabeling us to use shadows etc. in the game...

Someone else has already asked me about using this technique for
shadows. The reason why I can easily use it for shadows in my game
is because the whole landscape is created using shaded polygons so
it's not a big issue to have different shades in different parts
of the display. There are only 8 textures used and only 65 possible
polygon shapes. So these numbers were small enough to let me use
a few LUT's to speed up the shading calculations. In fact the whole
shading effect is held in 65 look up tables! (4K each). Now, if you
were using squares then you only have one shape and so you might
be able to use just one look up table.

It's not easy to simply suggest a shading method for everyone to
use because every game has different needs. For an example I could
use a game like Mario64 because most of us have seen such a game
if not the game itself. Mario64 would have close to infinite different
polygon shapes so no 'shape based' pre-calculations would be possible.
A quick look at the game showed that the world is either textured
with no shading or non-textured with shading. So they have basic
texture mapping and basic gouraud shaded colour polygons. A game
with a small number of textures would be ideal for pre calculating
all the textures in various shades. This is another method I use
in Foundation. The 8 textures are pre-calculated in 16 shades from
normal->almost black. So, for many games there are "limitations" that
can be used when you`re thinking about utilizing a look up table to
achieve a desired effect.

I must reiterate my point about LUT's not being such a bad thing. Take
something as simple as textures. Imagine I have 8 textures and they`re
64x60 in 256 colours chunky format. You might think of these as shapes
but really they`re just 64x60 look up tables! In fact any chunky object
is really just a LUT containing colour values. So now Imagine that we
have a shape which coesn`t contain colour values but instead contains
shading values. Now sudenly it's not a shape, it's an evil LUT! ;)

The idea behind gouraud shading is to blend all the polygons (or
any shape for that matter) together where they join. In the case
of a 3D display you would probably be calculating the light values
of each corner of the shape and then create a smooth gradient between
these points. So the shading is all done inside the shape so when
all the shapes join together you don`t really notice the joins so
much. Gouraud shading uses the light/colour values at the edges and
creates a perfect gradient from the left edge to the right edge
and then continues down until all the lines of the shape are shaded.

Moving away from the traditional real-time Gouraud tecnique you
can consider exactly what you want to achieve and then look at
how you might be able to do it. This seems like an obvious statement
but really it's the only way you can tackle any unique task. Is
the game using texture mapping or pre-rendred shapes. Does it
use a wide range of different shapes like 3d polygons or warped
squares or does it use traditional "blocks". I was very lucky
when I tackled this shading problem in Foundation. At the time
I was only using 5 textures and 65 shapes. The old version of
the game was using (65 * 5) pre-calculated shapes so I had a
lot of previously wasted memory to play with. In the end I decided
to use 65 shapes which contain the shading information for each
shape and then I pre-calculated the textures (I even added 3 new
ones) to 16 shades. In the end I was left with 65 + (8 * 16) shapes
which is a big saving over the pre-calculated method. To breifly
explain what my pre-shaded shapes are, They contain brightness
values which tell me which shade of texture to use. So, if the
pre-shaded shape contained 6,5,5,4,3,2,2,1 I would render a pixel
from texture 6, two from texture 5 and so on. This sounds like
a complicated system but it is doing quite a lot of work. It
renders a shape with simple texture mapping, shading, lighting
and blending all in one go. All the shading/blending/lighting
calculations are done once (before the game starts).

Once again, this technique works perfectly for my game but another
game with different needs would most likely require a different
method but relly it's all about how best to utilize a few LUT's.
I was lucky because all the object in my game (buildings, people,
trees etc.) already had variable brightness in real-ltime so
it all worked well with the new texturing. If you add lighting to
a game it has to be done to every object and not just the background.

Cheers,

Paul

-- =

< Paul Burkey http://www.sneech.freeserve.co.uk >


