@NODE "Mail_803" "signed/unsigned"
 for scott@online.u-net.com; Sat, 24 Apr 1999 13:03:30 +0100
From: Curt Esser <camge@ix.netcom.com>
Date: Sat, 24 Apr 1999 06:52:58 -0500
Subject: signed/unsigned

Hi James

On 24-Apr-99, James L Boyd wrote:
> Curt Esser churned out *this* drivel:
> 
>> Overflow Errors are not "real" errors - it has to do with Blitz's
>> insisting that all variables are signed.
>> 
>> For example, this will cause an Overflow Error:
>> 
>> a.b=200  because Blitz thinks a byte can only be + or - 127
>> 
>> But the correct byte (or rather bits) is stored anyway:
>> 
>> NPrint a.b AND $FF will return 200.
> 
> So what's the "real" range for a byte then?

Unsigned byte = 0/255
Unsigned word = 0/65535
Unsigned long = 0/4294967295
> 
>> In other words, if you are calling a System routine that needs an
>> unsigned Word, just turn off overflow errors, put the required number
>> into the Word, and don't worry about it...
> 
> That's handy to know, but can you explain signed and unsigned again
> for me? :)

Signed means that the last bit (or is it the first?) is read as a + or -
sign.
Unsigned uses that bit simply as another part of the number, so you can get
twice as much "number" out of it, but it is always positive.

But either way it's read, the bits are the same.  So if you need to use an
unsigned byte for a system routine, who cares if Blitz thinks it's signed? 
The system will still read it correctly.

If you need to do some calculations with it in Blitz, you're better to
convert it to a word:

a.b=(value from a system routine)
aw.w=a.b AND $FF

now do the calculations on the word...

when you're done, you can put it back in the byte for the system:

a.b=a.w  ;here is where Blitz would give the Overflow Error

To convert a word to a long, it is  aw.w AND $FFFF

If you need to calculate something with an unsigned long, I guess you'll
have to learn "C" or Assembler or something...

                                    Yours electronically,
                                    Curt Esser
                                    camge@ix.netcom.com
                                    http://members.xoom.com/Curt_Esser/



