@NODE "Mail_804" "Re: signed/unsigned"
 for scott@online.u-net.com; Sat, 24 Apr 1999 17:21:18 +0100
From: "David McMinn" <D.Mcminn@eee.rgu.ac.uk>
Organization: The Robert Gordon University, E&EE
Date: Sat, 24 Apr 1999 17:19:44 +0100
encoding: Quoted-printable
Subject: Re: signed/unsigned

> Signed means that the last bit (or is it the first?) is read as a + or -
> sign. Unsigned uses that bit simply as another part of the number, so yo=
u
> can get twice as much "number" out of it, but it is always positive.

Its the most significant bit. And its not just a + or - sign, with signed 
numbers, they are treated as two's complement. The MSB in an unsigned bte =
would 
represent +128, but signed it would be -128.


