@NODE "Mail_806" "Re: signed/unsigned"
 for scott@online.u-net.com; Sun, 25 Apr 1999 02:10:17 +0000
From: "Anders Hasselqvist" <hassel@acc.umu.se>
Subject: Re: signed/unsigned
Date: Sun, 25 Apr 1999 03:09:30 +0200
	charset="iso-8859-1"
Encoding: quoted-printable

From: Curt Esser <camge@ix.netcom.com>


> Hi David
>=20
>>
> > Its the most significant bit. And its not just a + or - sign, with =
signed
> > numbers, they are treated as two's complement. The MSB in an =
unsigned bte
> > would represent +128, but signed it would be -128.
>=20
> Oooppsss!  Well, it's not the first time I've been completely off  ;)
>=20
>

Well, David is not entirely correct ;)
The maximum positive value a signed byte can represent is 127 =3D %0111 =
1111.
The next value is -1 represented as %1111 1111.

Since you only need one 0 representation there is no -0.
Therefore the minimum negative value is -128 =3D %1000 0000.

Bye,

Anders Hasselqvist
hassel@acc.umu.se




