@NODE "Mail_816" "Spline Audio Compression"
 for scott@online.u-net.com; Sat, 17 Apr 1999 11:29:57 +0100
From: Jamie Bentley <sniper@technet2000.com.au>
Date: Sat, 14 Jan 1978 03:33:15 +0500
Organization: Sniper Productions
Subject: Spline Audio Compression

 Yes, it sounds stupid, but someone tried it.

 I don't know how well it worked.

 If your compression simple instruments, making "key points" and making
everything in-between spline based (like a graphical representation) would
save  MASSIVE amounts and would not be subject to quality (it could be
stretched or shrunk easily).

 Ie, if a sound wave naturally goes from (in this case) 01 to 300 to 01, the
storage medium would have to count it all like 01,02,03,04,05...... where's
four keypoints would keep shrink its size by 400% or more.

 Not to mention the fact that less key points would have to be used it you had
a few different kind of splines or linear betweens.

 If you have more interest in my theory email me and I'll send you some
diagrams :)

 Anyway, as more mixing, it might not be a good idea because as the intruments
combined more points would be needed until its probably best to leave it  the
way it is, but as for singular instruments (especially bass drums, flutes and
strings, and piano samples, and voice for that matter) you'd be looking at
something much more effecient than MP3 :)

 Jamie Bentley


