>> 
>> If you have more interest in my theory email me and I'll send you
>> some diagrams :)
> 
>  Yes please- that would be interesting- you might be able to apply it
>to speech- I don't know.

  IMHO spline based compression will prove to be inefficient in the case
of the complex waveforms which comprise most natural sounds.  If things
were simplified enough to get worthwhile compression you would lose most
of the timbre and overtones which comprise the rich fullness of natural
sound and would be left with very artificial tones.  It should work very
well with more "pure" electronic tones however.
  Don't let this stop you from trying if you want to though.  I could be
supprised, and that would be a nice surprise.  It's just that I have a
great deal of experiance with electronic sound reproduction and I know
that every little variance and anomoly contributes to the naturalness of
the sound, and removing any of them triggers a subconsious flag in the
brain of the hearer which says that something doesn't add up.  Many
anomolys in sounds are caused by the echos and reflections from the
surrounding area, and the brain picks up on any conflicts in the aural
"picture" that they "paint" of the surrounding reflecting surfaces, even
though the listener isn't fully cognisant of the reason the sound doesn't
quite seem right.
  I am certainly not saying that I am possitive there is no way to make it
work.  If you discover a way you may hit upon something very useful.


cach y'all later,

Donovan Reeve (bubby.lnk@ispi.net)



