@NODE "Mail_825" "Re: string compression"
 for scott@online.u-net.com; Tue, 13 Apr 1999 17:59:59 +0100
From: "Dave" <dave@nbsamiga.demon.co.uk>
Subject: Re: string compression
Date: Tue, 13 Apr 1999 17:55:26 +0100
	charset="iso-8859-1"
Encoding: 7bit

>Hi.
>
>I dont suppose anyone here knows anything about optimising string
>compression? I need to do searches at 65536 different starting
>offsets, with potential length up to 4k (in longwords). At worst this
>can mean 260 megabytes of memory access just to find the longest
>repeated string. I need very much to cut this down. any ideas?


What do you mean..just text strings..or any character strings (0-256)??

>i tried looking at lzw type compression but i can't understand it


hmmm...okay...I have a few mins (lol)....try this

Imagine you have 4 different possible codes (A, B, C, D)...first you decide
how many table entries you`ll allow...(ie, how many different strings you
can have in the table..say 12 bit - 4096 entries), and then initialize the
table such that

0 = A, 1 = B,  2 = C, 3 = D

Now say you have a character stream to compress....ABACBADCBBAD

You take the each character in turn, starting with the first just as a
single character, and then progress through the characters while comparing
with strings already in the table. (Char stream is the input, Comp STream is
the compressed output if any for the current charstring, Table is the new
addition to the table if any!)

CharStream      -      CompStream      -    Table
A                       -                                    -
(A)B                 -        0                           -    4 = AB
(B)A                  -        1                          -    5 = BA
(A)C                  -        0                          -    6 = AC
(C)B                  -        2                          -    7 = CB
(B)A                  -                                    -
(BA)D                -        5                          -    8 = BAD
(D)C                  -         3                           -    9 = DC
(C)B                  -                                     -
(CB)B                -        7                          -    10=CBB
(B)A                   -                                    -
(BA)D                -        8                          -

Basically, you start with a char from the stream, and add the next character
from the input to it, and keep doing that while you find the cumalative
string in the table, otherwise you output the newest character to the decode
stream, and add the new string to the table. This way you can rebuild the
table from the data, rather than having a table saved with your data when
you need to decompress it (ie, smaller size!)....ps...watch out for ultra
long strings...you`d be better off setting a string length limit (a fairly
big limit..but it allows the compression to break up small repetative
sections into more useable chucks and doesn`t waste table space!)....as it
gets worse as it gets longer ;).......

Things to watch out for...table overflow....string comparing effeciency
(theres a good way to do it, and a bad way) and table memory usage....(the
best way is to make the table store a pointer to the previous part of the
string in the table, instead of storing all the different string variations
in the table memory, and then have the new character added on the
end.....tricky to explain..but the only worthwhile way of doing it)

Sorry for the wobbly table...anyone know how to make outsuck express
better??

Dave













>--
>Paul.
