@NODE "Mail_827" "string compression"
 for scott@online.u-net.com; Tue, 13 Apr 1999 22:38:33 +0100
From: "Paul" <paulwest@stationone.demon.co.uk>
Organization: private
Date: 13 Apr 99 19:49:47 +0000
Subject: string compression
Encoding: 7bit

Hi.

Thanks to those who have offered help with the string compression,
mainly Dave and Sami. However, your suggestions unfortunately don't
help matters. I am compressing images, not text files, and the
string compression is intermixed with other types of compression and
has to decompress fast. Allow me to elaborate..

I am working on a new animation format like I said. Well, actions
speak louder than words and everyone else seemed only to talk about
it. <g> I am starting off with a straightforward program with no GUI
other than asl requesters for filenames and screenmode, that takes an
IFF Anim5 or Anim7 file (using RIAnim lib). It converts the anim to
chunky on the fly and then sets about compressing it.

Now, my main theory behind the compression is two things. Firstly, IFF
anim compression includes new data in the file if the image has
changed since the previous frame. This means that anything that moves
equates to extra filesize. To target this I am going to add
repetition-string compression to the other opcodes, namely `skip',
`byterun', and `byte sequence' that are present in the Anim7 format.
Now, these various methods are working fine, but the problem comes
with the new repetition compression that I am trying to get working.
I've written such a routine before and it was just as problematical
then. My other basis for increasing compression is that there is a
history buffer, in which are the previous 16 (currently) frames of the
animation interleaved together. This is to provide the repetition
search with far more `likely' local data in which to find repeated
strings (sequences of pixels).

To give some idea of the amount of work to be done, consider this: The
compressor goes through the current frame of the animation in a fairly
ordinary X and Y loop. At the current coordinates, the data which
follows has to first be searched to see if it can be byterun encoded
(a sequence of pixels the same colour), and wether it can be
skipped/rubbed through (the pixels are the same at the same
coordinates in the previous frame, ie no delta change). This is fairly
simple, but then comes the repetition search. There are 65536
potential offsets, which is a signed word value added to the address
of mem of the current coordinates in the X and Y loop. This is so that
the data can be searched +- 32767 bytes backwards or forwards to find
repeated data. Firstly only the first byte at each offset is compared
to the pixel at X,Y. This alone is 65536 byte comparisons, but is
nothing compared to what follows. If one of the offsets contains the
same colour pixel as at X,Y, then a search ensues based upon that
offset and proceeding for up to 4096 bytes forwards from that point.
While this occurs all of the bytes have to be compared with the
sequence of pixels from X,Y onwards. The end result is to figure out
where, within the offset limits, you can find the longest instance of
a sequence of pixels which match those at the current X,Y position.
This offset and string length would then be made into an opcode. At
this point, the longest method out of byterun, rubthrough and
repetition is found and the length of the best method is added to the
X,Y coords (it wraps around the edges of the bitmap of course). Then
the whole thing begins again.

Now, although slow, it tends to work okay for fairly changing
animations with not very long byteruns. However, the nightmare begins
when you start to have images with large expanses of the same colour,
such as cartoony type things, computer generated images, etc. When
there are a lot of pixels the same colour, the potential length of a
repetition sequence becomes large, and this massively increases the
amount of memory access involved in finding the longest match. At
worst, I think it turns out that there could be about 260 *megabytes*
of memory-access to find just ONE string! This would occur if, say,
you were searching a piece of black sky, the background for a rayraced
anim perhaps, and particularly cartoon anims. When big expanses of
colour occur like that the compression slows down to a halt which
makes it completely impractical.

There are a few methods I have devised so far to get around this
problem. If a byterun is found of a fairly long length, say 64 pixels,
then I skip the repetition search entirely. The same applies to a
rubthrough area. If the byterun or rubthrough is as long or longer
than the longest possible repetition then it will also skip the
search. Then the only final thing I can do is make a quick search in
the current frame from X,Y onwards, up to the potential maximum length
of repetition string, and as i go I keep track of wether the pixels in
the string are the same colour or not. I have a threshold of, say, 32
pixels, and if more than 32 pixels are of the same colour adjacently
then I bring into play a restraint on the size limit of the
repetition strings. This causes the rep search to be sped up
tremendously, particularly for example if the anim has a black sky
with small stars... the byterun wouldn't detect it but the repetition
search may have tried to find a string that started with a couple of
differently coloured pixels followed by a massive expanse of space. So
that's sort of nipped the problem in the but, except it probably
contributes a little to the overall filesize and doesn't leave me
waiting for several hours for a single frame to compress.

But, it is here that I ask if anyone has any other suggestions about
how to make the compression more efficient without losing further
compression size.

At the moment I have generated an output file, of a single anim frame
from a few anims. It's not looking too bad (there is a small bug in
the compress somewhere atm). A frame from a Tobias Richter startrek
anim ("disconnect"), which is one of those anims generated with
flat-filled 3d polygons, compresses from a frame size (raw) of about
90000 bytes down to about 1200 bytes (1:75?). BUT, that's because
there are a LOT of areas of the same colour, very little texture at
all. It's about 3 times smaller than the IFF anim5 size for that
frame. Alternatively, a frame from a raytraced anim of a walking mouse
in front of a backdrop, with pretty bad dithering, is 25k as anim5 or
about 15k in my compressed format (original size of 64000 bytes). So a
ratio of, say, 1:4. I still have a few tricks up my sleeve and this is
sizes for longword-based compression (byte and word are generally
smaller). So overall it's not looking too bad. I think the target was
22k per frame was it? Hmm, well not too bad so far and it should
decompress very fast.

Anyway, if you can think of any helpful ideas let me know.

-- 
Paul.

