From: Paul Burkey <burkey@bigfoot.com>
X-Accept-Language: en
Subject: Re: string compression
Encoding: 7bit

Paul wrote:
> But, it is here that I ask if anyone has any other suggestions about
> how to make the compression more efficient without losing further
> compression size.

The animation format of Foundation uses the same compression routines I
use for all other files in the game. It's a special Blitz compression
lib which was donated to me by a good friend of mine. The lib is not
available for public use but he may be persuaded to let the lib out
for general usage. I mention this because the compression was never
designed specifically for real-time animation's but does have very
fast decompression (based on the Imploder algorithm) but it may
not be the best choice for this particular type of data. The data
stored in animation's are usually delta codes which compress very
well. This reminds me of the mp3 format which has a serious flaw
where 10 minutes of CD quality *silence* would result in an mp3 of
approx. 2.8Meg in size while the same sample in wav format (originally
31Meg in size) will compress to only with 136k with Zip. Does this
mean mp3 is bad at compressing sound? of course not! But it shows
how some compression methods are well suited to complex data while
others are well suited to sparse data. This is why I'm not in a
rush to push my compression system onto you for your own anim format.

> At the moment I have generated an output file, of a single anim frame
> from a few anims. It's not looking too bad (there is a small bug in
> the compress somewhere atm). A frame from a Tobias Richter startrek
> anim ("disconnect"), which is one of those anims generated with
> flat-filled 3d polygons, compresses from a frame size (raw) of about
> 90000 bytes down to about 1200 bytes (1:75?). BUT, that's because
> there are a LOT of areas of the same colour, very little texture at
> all. It's about 3 times smaller than the IFF anim5 size for that
> frame.

I found this with my own anim format. It would work very well on
other peoples animation's but not so good on my own anim :) Anyone
who has seen Foundations intro will spot the slow panning camera
movement which puts a stop to most static image space! :)

> Alternatively, a frame from a raytraced anim of a walking mouse
> in front of a backdrop, with pretty bad dithering, is 25k as anim5 or
> about 15k in my compressed format (original size of 64000 bytes). So a
> ratio of, say, 1:4. I still have a few tricks up my sleeve and this is
> sizes for longword-based compression (byte and word are generally
> smaller). So overall it's not looking too bad. I think the target was
> 22k per frame was it? Hmm, well not too bad so far and it should
> decompress very fast.

I use two anims in Foundation, one with about 2% loss of quality
and one with 10% loss which looks pretty bad. The high quality anim
is 21k per frame and the lower quality anim is just 12k per frame.
So, my problem was never with the data size but the parsing. As I
mentioned to you the other day on IRC, I can't stress how important
it is to implement asynchronous data access. I could probably have
almost doubled the speed of my anim playback if I had done that. It's
too late for me to improve that now but it's a lesson I learnt that
I have to pass on! I'm a strong believer in the "naive approach to
problem solving" which is to say that too much input from me might
spoil the chances of you discovering a better anim format.

When you're getting closer to a good result I'd like to convert one
of your anims to my own anim format so we can benchmark the two
methods. We can compare anim sizes and playback speeds which could
give us both the incentive to optimize further.

Cheers,

Paul

-- 
< Paul Burkey http://www.sneech.freeserve.co.uk >


