>  other than asl requesters for filenames and screenmode, that takes an
>  IFF Anim5 or Anim7 file (using RIAnim lib). It converts the anim to
>  chunky on the fly and then sets about compressing it.

>  Now, my main theory behind the compression is two things. Firstly, IFF=

>  anim compression includes new data in the file if the image has
>  changed since the previous frame. This means that anything that moves
>  equates to extra filesize. To target this I am going to add
>  repetition-string compression to the other opcodes, namely `skip',
>  `byterun', and `byte sequence' that are present in the Anim7 format.
>  Now, these various methods are working fine, but the problem comes
>  with the new repetition compression that I am trying to get working.
>  I've written such a routine before and it was just as problematical
>  then. My other basis for increasing compression is that there is a
>  history buffer, in which are the previous 16 (currently) frames of the=

>  animation interleaved together. This is to provide the repetition
>  search with far more `likely' local data in which to find repeated
>  strings (sequences of pixels).

Well Could you simply run the rle and rub through to the frame and then
compare these repetitive sections to previous frames it would be faster a=
nd
I think it could lead to even smaller size.

For example:

you have two to 16  rle + skip compressed frames now you start to replace=

these later frames rle+skip sequences with repeting info so you have in o=
ne
previous frame that have "rle 14 bytes, let 16 as it is, then skip 10 byt=
es,
rle 14 bytes, let 16 as it it, skip then bytes" So if you find this kind =
of
matches from previous frames you simply point the word pointer to there.

You could possibly check before the last key frame too, but it would
prevent the skipping of frames and thus the key frame thingy all together=
=2E


This may illustrate the idea beter:

RLE8+SKIP4+DATA16+RLE6+SKIP6

and if we have this same sequence repeated later in some where, we simply=

point to it using Repeat. And repeats could be started in the midle off
DATA blocks too if they are long.

But now to the REAL searching problem. =


Have you tried to use QUICKSORT? Asm code can be found from the aminet.

If you want I have this Compression FAQ, which considers various compress=
ing
issues?  =

