Subject: Re: string compression

Hi Paul

On 13-Apr-99, Paul wrote:

> However, the nightmare begins
> when you start to have images with large expanses of the same colour,
> such as cartoony type things, computer generated images, etc. When
> there are a lot of pixels the same colour, the potential length of a
> repetition sequence becomes large, and this massively increases the
> amount of memory access involved in finding the longest match. At
> worst, I think it turns out that there could be about 260 *megabytes*
> of memory-access to find just ONE string! This would occur if, say,
> you were searching a piece of black sky, the background for a rayraced
> anim perhaps, and particularly cartoon anims. When big expanses of
> colour occur like that the compression slows down to a halt which
> makes it completely impractical.
 
Well in my CNKI format i used a technique of only saving the changes
from the previous frame, in order to do this you have to lose a number
from your byte ie 1 less colour in 256 colour palette.

The second part to my compression works like this:
Instead of having one byte, i have 2 bytes.
The first byte tells you how many pixels the colour lasts for with a
max of 256, and the second tells you what colour it is.
Because of the first method, you already have big chunks of byte 255
so there for the compression can say that colour 255 lasts for 255
pixels before puting another 'FFFF' (hex).

This can have some very good compression ratios indeed :) 4.5k to 800 bytes

Cheers,

Chris.
