On 15-Apr-99, Paul wrote:
>>  What could be done is have intelligent placing of keyframes ie:
>> only put a new one in, when the new frame has changed significantly.
>> Or has changed significantly from the last keyframe.
> 
> How would keyframes have anything to do with lossless compression?

  Ah I see, you only do repetition compression every 16 frames, I was
assuming you did delta compression from every 16th frame as well :-)
  Would doing delta compression from keyframes (calculated intelligently
ie: when you had a large change in picture), help in compression, or
would it make the file size bigger? If you did have delta keyframes,
you could then do your repetition compression between keyframes instead
of every 16th frame.
  Maybe even if you didn't use delta keyframes, could you use repetition
keyframes (ie: variable on the changes between frames instead of every
16 frames).
  I'm rather interested in this, as later on (much later on ;), I would
like to have a look into sound compression for real time multi-player
game conversations (as some PC games now have).
   Sound is apparently hard to compress there's not much repetition, but
they've seemed to have been able to compress it a lot to allow it on
LANs and even through the net!

  Seeya- Anton

