@NODE "Mail_842" "Re: string compression"
 for scott@online.u-net.com; Thu, 15 Apr 1999 17:35:18 +0100
From: "Dave" <dave@nbsamiga.demon.co.uk>
Subject: Re: string compression
Date: Thu, 15 Apr 1999 17:34:11 +0100
	charset="iso-8859-1"
Encoding: 7bit

>There was recently something posted on Aminet about Fibnoccai compression
>for sound samples - I didn't pay attention to what it was, but maybe it
>would be of some interest.  I probably spelled it wrong too - it's that
>method that is supposedly available on 8svx/iff sounds, though I've never
>seen a compressed 8svx sample...


Hi Curt,

 You must have seen a compressed 8svx?? audiomaster writes them when you ask
it to......Fibonacci compression is the 4 bit delta of a single 8 byte
sample (ie, you ge 50% compression always). But the problem is, it`s not
quite the same as normal delta. Basically the first byte is a real byte
(-128 to +128) and then the next byte is two 4 bit deltas. The first delta
modifys the first byte, then the second modifys the new byte...and you have
3 bytes from 2. The problem is with encoding...as you only have 4 bit delta
precision...as you compress the sample...you may find you reach a lot of
points in the sample which are way out side the data range...then what
happens is you need to go back to the start and flatten out the sample..so
it`ll fit better using delta. This can happen over and over...causing a lot
of time to be wasted. If you don`t do that...well, I don`t know...it`d sound
pretty bad I`d guess ;)......there are other sound compression routines, and
8svx is VERY old.....but it`s simple and you are always getting 50%
compression!

On the subject of sound...how safe do you think it is to queue up blank
sample banks to the audio device, and fill them in as the audio device is
playing them?? (hopefully before it`s playing them...or while it`s in an
earlier part of the block)......fairly os safe...or a something that will
cause my player to die a death on various machines??

Dave



