Well, well Paul Burkey, OK then but=2E=2E=2E
> Paul wrote:
> > But, it is here that I ask if anyone has any other suggestions about
> > how to make the compression more efficient without losing further
> > compression size=2E
>=20
> The animation format of Foundation uses the same compression routines I
> use for all other files in the game=2E It's a special Blitz compression
> lib which was donated to me by a good friend of mine=2E The lib is not
> available for public use but he may be persuaded to let the lib out
> for general usage=2E I mention this because the compression was never
> designed specifically for real-time animation's but does have very
> fast decompression (based on the Imploder algorithm) but it may
> not be the best choice for this particular type of data=2E The data
> stored in animation's are usually delta codes which compress very
> well=2E This reminds me of the mp3 format which has a serious flaw
> where 10 minutes of CD quality *silence* would result in an mp3 of
> approx=2E 2=2E8Meg in size while the same sample in wav format (originall=
y
> 31Meg in size) will compress to only with 136k with Zip=2E Does this
> mean mp3 is bad at compressing sound? of course not! But it shows
> how some compression methods are well suited to complex data while
> others are well suited to sparse data=2E This is why I'm not in a
> rush to push my compression system onto you for your own anim format=2E
>=20
Who say's you have to use just only one compresion system?  There is
