@NODE "Mail_870" "Re: Task List Questions"
 for scott@online.u-net.com; Sun, 4 Apr 1999 19:29:02 +0100
From: "David McMinn" <dmcminn@house-of-mojo.freeserve.co.uk>
Organization: International House of Mojo
Date: Sun, 4 Apr 1999 19:27:14 +0100
encoding: Quoted-printable
Subject: Re: Task List Questions

On 4 Apr 99, at 19:08, Simon broke out long enough to write:

> Why is it bad to have a peek at the task list?

Future compatibility, and all that. Shouldn't mess with it in case it brea=
ks, 
<lots of other scare-mongering lame-ass excuses>.

> But how do you find which Background CLI relates to which launched
> program?

 The node in the list is actually part of a task structure. So just do 
*task.Task =3D *node. There'll be flags there somewhere, check how to find=
 out 
what flag says that this task is actually a process. If it is a process th=
en 
you can safely say that the task newtype is part of the process one, so do=
 
*process.Process =3D *task. Then within that there's a BCPL pointer to a 
CommandLineInterface structure (BCPL pointers are longword aligned, so you=
 need 
to multiply it by 4 before getting the real pointer). Inside the 
CommandLineInterface newtype there's a program name field. Use it. No code=
 
though.


[) /\ \/ ][ [)   |\/| =A9 |\/| ][ |\| |\|
 dmcminn@house-of-mojo.freeserve.co.uk
