@NODE "Mail_896" "Video compression"
 for scott@online.u-net.com; Sat, 17 Apr 1999 03:46:15 +0000
From: Anton Reinauer <anton@ww.co.nz>
Date: Sat, 17 Apr 1999 14:24:13 +1200
Subject: Video compression

On 16-Apr-99, Dave wrote:

> but in video it works differently..well how I plan to do
> it...you decode the frame into 2x2 blocks...ie
> 
> 11 22 33 44
> 11 22 33 44
> 55 66 77 88
> 55 66 77 88
> 
> Then you simply keep the same chroma values for all pixels in the same
> square (I`ve not decided wether to use a mean value, or a biased
> value, or highest/lowest yet...depends after some testing)....so for
> the 4 1111 pixels, you have a Y (luminescence....it`s not...but that`s
> what most ppl will understand...and if you not it`s not..then you have
> no need for an explanation!) for each pixel (4 bytes) and 2 UV
> values...(2 Bytes).....as they should be closer. So you`ll similar
> shades of the same colour in a single 2x2 block....(ie blurs
> edges...hence lossy)...this give you better output to different rgb
> format in my opinion, instead of fixing it at say, 16 RGB....and then
> having the same colours, whether viewed under 16/24/32 bit. And still
> should be workable under 8 bit (though I`m not sure how good 2 bits of
> blue will be...but we`ll soon see!)....
 
  Is it a bit like HAM encoding?

-- 
        Anton Reinauer <anton@ww.co.nz>
      


