@NODE "Mail_915" "Re: WB Screen depth on gfx card"
 for scott@online.u-net.com; Wed, 21 Apr 1999 15:21:17 +0100
Date: Wed, 21 Apr 1999 15:12:56 +0100
From: Paul Burkey <burkey@bigfoot.com>
X-Accept-Language: en
Subject: Re: WB Screen depth on gfx card
Encoding: 7bit

Schnider Angel wrote:
> 
> Paul Burkey wrote:
> > Thats because the OS structures were not designed with RTG
> > screens in mind. If you want to find the real depth of the
> > screen you have to use the OS functions which are patched
> > by the RTG software (CyberGFX or Picasso96) to give you
> > the real values.
> >
> > Try:
> >
> >   depth = GetBitMapAttr_(*Screen\RastPort\BitMap,#BMA_DEPTH)
> >
> > Thats why it's always best to go through the OS compared to
> > peeking about in the structures.
>
> Hello I have a very basic question , What is the rastport ? and
> how can i use it ? thanks because iI 'm a novice.

A RastPort is really just a "Window of memory". Take a normal
Workbench window for example. The part of the window that
contains the 'graphics' is the windows RastPort. The Workbench
always has a window of it's own but most people use the
'Backdrop' feature to make the window appear as if it was
part of the screen itself. So, the part of the screen that
contains graphics is the screens RastPort. Most people have
used the WBlit or WPlot commands and they feel happy about
the concept of drawing graphics to a Window. However, one
thing some people don`t realize is that WPlot is realy
just an easy way to draw to the windows RastPort. So next
time you're drawing graphics to a Window you are really
rendering graphics to the Windows RastPort.

The graphics.library contains many functions that will render
graphics into a RastPort. The easiest of these are the
WritePixel_, Move_, Draw_, SetAPen_, functions. which give
you the ability to draw pixels, possition and draw lines and
set the Pen colour. You can get the rastport of you window
with RastPort(Window#) so you should now be able to open a
window and do some basic graphics.library rendering!

Of course, the RastPort doesn`t have to be connected to a
Window or a Screen but it usually is. You could allocate
some memory and create a rastport to 'point' into this
area of memory but we're getting into deeper waters there! 

I see David has given a much more detailed/technical
description of RastPorts along with pointers to the
graphics.library (autodocs) documentation. What more could
you ask for! :)

Cheers,

Paul
-- 
< Paul Burkey http://www.sneech.freeserve.co.uk >


