@NODE "Mail_927" "Re: What? Mildred? CNKI file format? naaa :)"
 for scott@online.u-net.com; Sun, 4 Apr 1999 18:10:44 +0100
From: Chris Deeney <chris@addnet.demon.co.uk>
Date: Sun, 04 Apr 1999 18:12:15 +0000
Organization: personal
Subject: Re: What? Mildred? CNKI file format? naaa :)

Hello Paul

On 04-Apr-99, Paul wrote:

> Good work, but how is it going to be useable if you're not allowed the
> full palette?

You can use the full 256 colours when coverting a brush. It isn't the added
compression thats the problem (the compression tooltype), its to do with
when converting animbrushes, instead of saving each frame of the animbrush
it only saves the changes from the previous frame - using byte(colour) 255
to indicate that a certain part of chunky is the same as the previous frame.
Initialy this doesn't alter the size of the file what so ever, but when the
compression is added, because of big chunks of FF(hex) in the file it has
some pretty bloody good compression on anim CNKI's :)

Once the anim CNKI is loaded into your proggy you can use the last 255 colour,
it's just for saving the anim CNKI you can't.

The only limitation is, when creating your animbrushes, just don't use colour
255
(if using a 256 colour palette)

Who uses all 256 colours when drawing shapes for a game? can u live without 1
colour
when creating your gfx in 256 colour mode, im sure i can :)

hope that clears up some missunderstandings ;)

cheers.

Chris.
-- 
