@NODE "Mail_928" "Whats a rastport (was WB Screen depth...)"
 for scott@online.u-net.com; Wed, 21 Apr 1999 11:15:17 +0100
From: "David McMinn" <D.Mcminn@eee.rgu.ac.uk>
Organization: The Robert Gordon University, E&EE
Date: Wed, 21 Apr 1999 11:12:29 +0100
encoding: Quoted-printable
Subject: Whats a rastport (was WB Screen depth...)

Hi

> Hello I have a very basic question , What is the rastport ? and how can =
i
> use it ? thanks because iI 'm a novice.

A rastport is something that the OS uses to draw on bitmaps. It basically 
stores all the information about the current drawing mode, colour, pattern=
s 
etc. It depends on what you are doing if you want to use it. If you don't =
have 
a blitz type bitmap, and can't use any blitz drawing commands, then you ma=
y 
need to set up a rastport to use for drawing.

 Also, if you have a window open, you can set the attributes of the rastpo=
rt to 
give you more drawing power than the blitz window drawing commands can all=
ow 
you.

To use one, you will need to create one, unless you are using the rastport=
 from 
a window or a screen as they will already be created for you. To create a 
rastport, you need to define a variable as a rastport type, initialise it,=
 and 
then point to a bitmap.

You need to include amigalibs.res as a resident.

DEFTYPE.RastPort rp        ; create our rastport
InitRastPort_ &rp          ; initialise it
rp\BitMap =3D Addr BitMap(0) ; tell rastport where to find our bitmap

 In the above code, I am assuming that the bitmap you are using is a Blitz=
 type 
bitmap, number 0. There are many other ways to create a bitmap, but this i=
s the 
simplest.

There are a lot of commands available for drawing using a rastport, read t=
he 
graphics.library autodoc. If you don't have it then you can try these URLs=
http://www.redrobe.demon.co.uk/amiga/essentials.html
http://www.amigaprog.freeserve.co.uk/essentials.html

 You should get the autodocs, probably the includes and the rkm libraries =
as 
well.

 When you are finished with the rastport, you don't need to free it (unles=
s you 
allocated memory for it, which you will not do using a variable like above=
).


|) /\ \/ ][ |)   |\/| =A9 |\/| ][ |\| |\|
