@NODE "Mail_941" "Re: Windows and their size dadgets"
 for scott@online.u-net.com; Tue, 27 Apr 1999 00:50:52 +0100
From: James L Boyd <jamesboyd@all-hail.freeserve.co.uk>
Date: Tue, 27 Apr 1999 00:47:52 +0000
Subject: Re: Windows and their size dadgets

--BOUNDARY.1747946872.2

Gareth Griffiths churned out *this* drivel:

>   Is there an OS call to change the size of a window without using the
> gadget?

#ChangeWindowBox_#

> I regularly boot with no startup to save mem on net stuff, but can't be
> arsed to change the AmigaDOS window so that the screen titlebar is
> visible. Can u change this in blitz and then quit the program so that the
> changes are still there?

Easy! Doesn't even cause any Enforcer hits :) See attached...

It'll only have an effect when a window called AmigaDOS is on screen,
eg. like when you boot with no startup :)

Unpack the StartHack program and stick it in your C: drawer, and
call it by typing :

    StartHack x y width height

eg. StartHack 0 11 640 150

Put it in a script file to make it even easier...

Source is in there...

Oh,#ChangeWindowBox_# isn't picky if you get the sizes wrong either ;)
 
See ya,
-- 
