@NODE "Mail_951" "Re: Windows with the OS!"
 for scott@online.u-net.com; Sun, 18 Apr 1999 18:26:41 +0100
From: "Dave" <dave@nbsamiga.demon.co.uk>
Subject: Re: Windows with the OS!
Date: Sun, 18 Apr 1999 18:25:45 +0100
	charset="iso-8859-1"
Encoding: 7bit

Hi David,


>> normal blitz commands with the windows. You can`t use the WaitEvent, or
>> Event commands, or access the Gadget value, but I have supplied my own
>> version of these commands. As far as I can tell, the only things that
>
>I know I said that as well, but I think you can hack it in a really bad way
so
>that it does work.


Hmmm, well my include was a start of a windows replacement, as 2.0 had some
funny os bugs...but then I got 2.1 and left it alone. It handles it`s own
win messages and doesn`t really hack into the blitz system, and thats why
the wait event, and event commands don`t work...but mine do, and there are
almost identical (and with one less bug too...remember rawkey (or is it
rawcode) anyone well unlike blitz mine works..woohoo!!)....I open my own
msgport, and handle the events by hand, instead of trying to patch the blitz
message port. (and that`s why cycle gadgets and radio buttons don`t work, as
blitz controls them after it`s received a gadget event)

>How does Blitz deal with objects, does it just allocate enough memory to
store
>them, then use as necessary. That might be that way, as when you look at
the
>objects from the debugger, the unused ones have addresses.


Ummm...basically it allocates a block of mem (maximum windows*sizeof
.window) at the start, which is the list of blitz windows. That`s why object
lists maximums are fixed at compile time, and why you can only have 2000`odd
items (something like that anyway) (cos it does a lsl.w
#window_multiplier_shift which is a rubbish thing to do, but gives fast
access to any blitz object in asm!)

>Anyway, if thats true, you can Poke.l Addr Window(0),*winaddr where
*winaddr
>is the result of the OpenWindow_ call. There's also a couple of other
things in
>there, like the current position for NPrint and Print and a pointer for
mouse
>pointer data. Check out bb2objtypes.res.


And that`s exactly what It does :).....but you also need a hook in the
window to a msg port...and you`d have to either make your own..like I did
(ie, non hacky way) or patch blitz`s msgport (which you`d have to find
first). That`s how blitz event and waitevent work. Other than that my
windows work just like normal for the rest of the commands.

Dave



