 for scott@online.u-net.com; Fri, 30 Apr 1999 03:06:20 +0100
Date: Fri, 30 Apr 1999 02:03:37 +0100
From: Paul Burkey <burkey@bigfoot.com>
X-Accept-Language: en
Subject: Re: Wotsits and pinball algorithm
Encoding: 7bit

Linda Bell wrote:
> OFF TOPIC
> Does anyone know what the hidden and undeletable file called
> "index.dat" is for in Temporary Internet Files in Windows?  I only
> know it`s there because I went into dos - it grows every time I`m
> on the net.  I`ve a mind to change the file attributes and delete
> it, just to see what happens.  Windows won`t allow me to delete
> it, and it`s archived as well.

wow, Windows questions in the blitz-list. Times are changing ;)

It's a log file that keeps track of what you`re up to on
the internet and every 6 months it gets secretly posted off
to the FBI and MI5 so big brother can make this world a
better place! ;)

But Microsoft would prefer you to think:-

It's the index for your cached Internet files. It's a bit like the
"GlobalCache" file that IBrowse uses and it wouldn`t be a good
idea to delete it which is why protected! :) You can remove the
cached files and alter the way Internet caching works with Internet
icon in the Windows Control Panel.

Cheers,

Paul

-- 
< Paul Burkey http://www.sneech.freeserve.co.uk >


